const scenarios3 = {
  7: [
    {
      text: "The Cheka, led by Dzerzhinsky, has begun the Red Terror in response to the assassination attempt on Lenin by Fanny Kaplan. Mass executions of 'class enemies' are underway. Some Bolsheviks welcome the terror as revolutionary necessity; others fear it will consume the revolution itself. A Cheka officer requests your signature on a list of hostages to be shot in reprisal.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Sign the list without hesitation — the revolution must defend itself by any means necessary.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -10, survival: 0.9, response: "You sign. Hundreds are executed. Dzerzhinsky marks you as a reliable comrade. The Red Terror escalates throughout the autumn of 1918, and your willingness to sanction it places you firmly within the revolutionary inner circle."},
        {text: "Refuse to sign — extrajudicial killings violate the principles we fought for.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -10, reputation: 15, survival: 0.6, response: "You refuse on principle. The Cheka proceeds regardless. Your moral stand earns respect among some old Bolsheviks, but Dzerzhinsky considers you unreliable. In a civil war, those who hesitate are suspect."},
        {text: "Sign but quietly remove several names from the list, saving those you can.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You edit the list discreetly, sparing a few while appearing compliant. It is a small mercy in a merciless time. If your alterations are discovered, you could face accusations of aiding counter-revolution."},
        {text: "Propose that hostages be used for prisoner exchanges with the Whites rather than executed.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You suggest a pragmatic alternative. Some hostages are indeed exchanged, yielding captured Bolsheviks in return. Your practical thinking impresses Lenin, who values revolutionaries who can calculate rather than merely rage."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Left Socialist-Revolutionaries, furious over Brest-Litovsk, have assassinated German ambassador Count Mirbach in Moscow and briefly seized key buildings in an attempted uprising. The Bolsheviks suppress the revolt and arrest Left SR leaders. You must decide how to handle former Left SR allies in your local soviet.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Arrest all Left SRs in your district immediately — they are all potential insurgents.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 0, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You order mass arrests. Many of those detained had nothing to do with the uprising, but the crackdown demonstrates your decisiveness. The coalition with the Left SRs is finished forever."},
        {text: "Distinguish between those involved in the uprising and ordinary Left SR members — punish only the guilty.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.8, response: "You conduct a measured response, winning respect from moderates. However, hardliners in Moscow question whether your restraint conceals Left SR sympathies. Nuance is dangerous in revolutionary times."},
        {text: "Use the crisis to seize Left SR positions in the local soviet for your own allies.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You exploit the chaos to consolidate Bolshevik control, placing your people in every vacated seat. Lenin approves of such initiative. The one-party state is being built district by district."},
        {text: "Argue that the Left SR revolt proves Brest-Litovsk was a mistake that has split the revolutionary camp.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.65, response: "You use the crisis to relitigate the peace treaty debate. Lenin is furious — the treaty saved the revolution, and questioning it now aids the enemy. Your political timing is terrible."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Nationalization of industry is proceeding chaotically. Factory committees have seized plants, but production is collapsing without experienced managers. Some advocate keeping former bourgeois factory owners as technical directors under workers' supervision. Others demand pure workers' control. Your district's main munitions factory has ground to a halt.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Reinstate the former factory director under strict Bolshevik oversight — we need ammunition for the Civil War.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You pragmatically bring back the bourgeois expert. Production resumes. Lenin supports this approach, citing the need for 'bourgeois specialists' during the transition period. Workers grumble but shells are needed at the front."},
        {text: "Appoint a worker from the factory floor as director — the proletariat must learn to manage.", loyalty: 5, cunning: -5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.8, response: "You promote a worker to director. Production suffers initially but the ideological commitment is unquestionable. The factory becomes a showcase of workers' control — at least in the propaganda reports you send to Moscow."},
        {text: "Send in a Bolshevik commissar to run the factory by decree — efficiency through discipline.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You impose party authority directly. The commissar knows nothing about munitions but everything about obedience. This model of party-appointed management will become the Soviet standard for decades."},
        {text: "Propose a collective management board combining workers, engineers, and party representatives.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You create a committee solution. It satisfies no faction completely but keeps the factory running. Lenin privately notes that troikas of management are an effective compromise during the transition."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The party has officially changed its name from the Russian Social-Democratic Labour Party (Bolsheviks) to the Russian Communist Party (Bolsheviks). Now a debate erupts over the party's new program. Should it emphasize world revolution and the international proletariat, or focus on consolidating power in Russia? Bukharin pushes for a maximalist internationalist program.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support Bukharin's internationalist program — the revolution is meaningless without spreading worldwide.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 0, reputation: 10, survival: 0.8, response: "You back Bukharin's maximalist vision. Lenin thinks Bukharin is too theoretical — 'the biggest theoretician in the party' but also 'scholastic.' Your internationalism is noted but considered somewhat impractical given the civil war raging at home."},
        {text: "Back Lenin's more cautious approach — build a program that addresses Russian realities first.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You support Lenin's practical focus on immediate Russian conditions while maintaining internationalist rhetoric. The final program adopts this balanced approach. Siding with Lenin rarely fails."},
        {text: "Argue that the program should prioritize the military victory in the Civil War above all theoretical questions.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You cut through the theoretical debate with military urgency. With Kolchak, Denikin, and foreign interventionists threatening the revolution, your focus on survival resonates with delegates who have seen combat."},
        {text: "Propose adding detailed sections on nationalities policy — the empire's subject peoples must see the revolution as liberation.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.85, response: "You advocate for strong nationalities provisions. This aligns with Lenin's thinking and helps recruit non-Russian peoples to the Bolshevik cause. Stalin, the Commissar of Nationalities, takes note of your interest in his portfolio."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Food supplies in Petrograd and Moscow are desperately scarce. The Committees of the Poor (Kombedy) have been dispatched to the countryside to requisition grain from peasants, often at gunpoint. Reports reach you of peasant uprisings against the grain requisitioners. A delegation of workers from a Petrograd factory begs you to intervene — their families are starving.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Demand harsher requisitioning — the peasants are hoarding grain while workers starve.", loyalty: 10, cunning: -5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You call for ruthless grain collection. The Food Commissariat approves. More grain reaches the cities, but peasant resistance intensifies. You are building the policies of War Communism that will culminate in the Kronstadt revolt three years later."},
        {text: "Propose trading industrial goods for grain — give the peasants an incentive to sell.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You suggest what amounts to a market mechanism. Lenin rejects this for now — it smells of capitalism. But he will adopt exactly this approach with the NEP in 1921. You are ahead of your time, which is politically dangerous."},
        {text: "Organize armed worker detachments to supplement the Kombedy in the countryside.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You mobilize workers as grain requisitioners, framing it as class war — urban proletariat against rural kulaks. The detachments collect grain with mixed results. Some workers are horrified by the rural poverty they encounter."},
        {text: "Divert grain from military supplies to feed the Petrograd workers — the rear must hold.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.75, response: "You redirect some military grain reserves to civilian use. The workers are grateful, but Trotsky's War Commissariat is furious at the diversion. Feeding civilians at the expense of the army is a dangerous precedent during a civil war."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Foreign intervention complicates the Civil War. British, French, Japanese, and American troops have landed at various ports. The Czechoslovak Legion controls vast stretches of the Trans-Siberian Railway. Some Bolsheviks hope for revolutionary uprisings in the intervening countries. Others argue the revolution must rely solely on its own strength. How do you address the foreign threat?",
      choices: [
        {text: "Call for revolutionary agitation among the foreign intervention troops — turn the imperialist soldiers into allies.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You organize propaganda operations targeting foreign soldiers. Some French sailors in the Black Sea do mutiny in 1919. Your faith in international solidarity proves partially justified, earning you credibility with the internationalist wing."},
        {text: "Focus entirely on military preparation — defeat the Whites and the foreigners will withdraw.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You take the pragmatic military view. Strengthening the Red Army is the priority. Lenin agrees — the foreign powers have limited appetite for a prolonged Russian war. Your strategic clarity is appreciated."},
        {text: "Propose secret diplomatic contacts with individual foreign powers to split the intervention coalition.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You suggest exploiting rivalries among the intervening powers. Japan and America distrust each other in Siberia; Britain and France have different interests. This Machiavellian approach appeals to Lenin's pragmatic side."},
        {text: "Demand that the party denounce the intervention as proof that world capitalism will never peacefully coexist with socialism.", loyalty: 5, cunning: -5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You make an ideological speech about the inherent hostility of imperialism. It is doctrinally sound and earns applause, but does nothing to address the immediate military situation. Theory without practice is a luxury in wartime."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "A crisis erupts within the party over democratic centralism. Some delegates argue that the Central Committee has accumulated too much power and that local soviets and party cells are being reduced to rubber stamps. The Democratic Centralists demand genuine debate and election of officials. Lenin insists that wartime conditions require strict discipline and centralized command.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support Lenin's call for strict centralism — democratic niceties must wait until the war is won.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You back wartime centralism. Lenin's position prevails. The precedent of sacrificing democracy for discipline will outlast the Civil War by decades, becoming the permanent operating mode of the Soviet system."},
        {text: "Sympathize with the Democratic Centralists — the party must practice what it preaches about soviet democracy.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -5, reputation: 15, survival: 0.65, response: "You speak for internal democracy. Lenin privately tells you this is 'syndicalist nonsense' in wartime. Your principled stand wins admiration from a minority but marks you as insufficiently disciplined for the majority."},
        {text: "Propose a compromise — centralism for military decisions, democracy for local economic matters.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You try to split the difference. It is a reasonable position that satisfies neither camp fully. In practice, the boundary between military and economic decisions is impossible to maintain during a civil war."},
        {text: "Avoid the debate entirely by volunteering for a fact-finding mission to the Southern Front.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You escape the political minefield by heading to the front. The trip is genuinely dangerous but politically safe. When you return, the debate has moved on and you have front-line credentials to show for it."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The question of the Constituent Assembly lingers. The Bolsheviks dissolved it in January 1918 after winning only a quarter of the seats. Mensheviks and Right SRs still demand its restoration. Some within the party worry that governing without electoral legitimacy weakens the revolution's moral authority abroad. Others say soviets are a higher form of democracy.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Declare the Constituent Assembly a dead letter — soviet power is superior to bourgeois parliamentarism.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You deliver an orthodox defense of soviet democracy over parliamentary democracy. Lenin has already settled this question in theory and practice. Your speech adds nothing new but confirms your reliability."},
        {text: "Argue that new elections to the soviets should be held to refresh their democratic mandate.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.75, response: "You call for genuine soviet elections. This sounds democratic but threatens Bolshevik control — free elections to soviets in 1918 might produce Menshevik or SR majorities. The leadership views your proposal with suspicion."},
        {text: "Focus on expanding the franchise within the soviet system — draw more workers and poor peasants into governance.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You advocate broadening participation within the existing system rather than restoring the old one. This satisfies democratic impulses while maintaining Bolshevik control. A politically astute middle path."},
        {text: "Use the Constituent Assembly question to attack Menshevik and SR 'counter-revolutionaries' who cling to bourgeois democracy.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You turn the debate into an offensive against rival socialist parties. Denouncing Mensheviks is always safe in Bolshevik circles. Your aggressive posture wins approval from hardliners."}
      ]
    }
  ],
  8: [
    {
      text: "Trotsky's Red Army has swelled to over three million soldiers, but desertion is rampant. Harsh measures are proposed: execution of deserters, collective punishment of their families, and barrier troops behind the lines. Some party members are uneasy about applying terror to the army's own soldiers. As a member of the Revolutionary Military Council, you must weigh in.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support the harshest anti-desertion measures — discipline wins wars.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You back Trotsky's iron discipline. Desertion rates drop. The Red Army's fearsome reputation for punishing defectors helps hold the lines together during the desperate fighting of 1919."},
        {text: "Propose combining punishment with better conditions — troops desert because they are starving and lice-ridden.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.9, response: "You advocate addressing root causes alongside punishment. Improved rations and medical care for front-line troops reduce desertion more effectively than firing squads. Your practical humanitarianism is noted favorably."},
        {text: "Argue against collective punishment of families — it will turn the peasantry against us.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.8, response: "You oppose punishing families for individual desertion. Trotsky overrules you — the Civil War demands extreme measures. But your concern for popular support reflects genuine strategic thinking."},
        {text: "Volunteer to personally lead an anti-desertion commission at the front, making examples of captured deserters.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 0, reputation: -10, survival: 0.7, response: "You take on the grim task of hunting deserters. It is thankless, brutal work that earns you the fear of soldiers and the gratitude of commanders. Your willingness to do dirty work demonstrates commitment."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The debate over military specialists intensifies after several former Tsarist officers defect back to the Whites. Stalin and Voroshilov at Tsaritsyn (future Stalingrad) openly defy Trotsky's orders and refuse to work with specialists, running their own independent command. Lenin must mediate. You are asked to report on the situation.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Report honestly that Stalin's insubordination is causing military setbacks at Tsaritsyn.", loyalty: 5, cunning: -5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.75, response: "You tell the truth about the Tsaritsyn mess. Lenin recalls Stalin from the front. Trotsky is vindicated. But Stalin has a long memory, and you have placed yourself among those who opposed him in the Civil War."},
        {text: "File a vague report that avoids blaming either side — both approaches have merit.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You write a masterpiece of bureaucratic ambiguity. Neither Stalin nor Trotsky can claim you attacked them. In the factional wars ahead, having avoided clear sides in the Tsaritsyn dispute will serve you well."},
        {text: "Side with Stalin — proletarian commanders are more politically reliable than Tsarist holdovers.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You back Stalin's position on class-loyal commanders. Lenin overrules this view for now, but Stalin remembers his supporters. Voroshilov and Budyonny also note your solidarity."},
        {text: "Propose a systematic vetting process for military specialists — keep the competent ones, remove the unreliable.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You offer a systematic rather than ideological solution. Vet each officer individually based on performance and loyalty. This technocratic approach appeals to Lenin's practical side and avoids factional traps."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Communist International (Comintern) has just been founded in Moscow. Delegates from fledgling communist parties around the world attend. Zinoviev is made chairman. The expectation is that world revolution is imminent — Germany, Hungary, and Bavaria have all seen revolutionary uprisings. How do you approach the international dimension?",
      choices: [
        {text: "Throw yourself into Comintern work — world revolution is the party's highest purpose.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 0, reputation: 10, survival: 0.8, response: "You become active in Comintern affairs, working with foreign communists. The work is exciting but will become increasingly subordinated to Soviet state interests. Zinoviev, your patron in this arena, will eventually fall from power."},
        {text: "Focus on Russian affairs — the Civil War must be won before we can export revolution.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You politely decline international assignments, citing the urgent needs of the domestic struggle. This is the practical position. Those who become too identified with the Comintern sometimes lose touch with the real power struggles within the Russian party."},
        {text: "Use Comintern contacts to arrange material support from foreign sympathizers for the Civil War effort.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You leverage international connections for practical benefit — channeling funds, supplies, and intelligence from foreign communist parties to support the Russian war effort. Making international work serve domestic needs earns approval."},
        {text: "Argue that the Comintern should be truly international, not merely a tool of Russian foreign policy.", loyalty: -5, cunning: -5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.75, response: "You advocate for genuine internationalism within the Comintern. This principled position will become increasingly untenable as the Soviet state subordinates the Comintern to its own diplomatic interests throughout the 1920s."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "A devastating typhus epidemic is sweeping through both armies and the civilian population. Lenin declares that 'either the louse defeats socialism or socialism defeats the louse.' Medical infrastructure has collapsed. A proposal comes to divert resources from the front to combat the epidemic. The military opposes any reduction in war supplies.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Prioritize the epidemic — dead soldiers from typhus cannot fight anyway.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.85, response: "You argue that epidemic control is a military necessity. Lenin agrees that typhus threatens the revolution as much as Denikin. Resources are redirected to delousing stations and field hospitals. Your public health logic saves lives and earns respect."},
        {text: "The front must come first — Denikin is advancing on Moscow and every resource must go to stopping him.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 0, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You back the military's demand for priority. The White advance is indeed existential. But typhus continues to ravage the rear, and the human cost of neglecting the epidemic is staggering."},
        {text: "Propose forced quarantine measures — isolate the sick ruthlessly to protect the healthy.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You advocate harsh quarantine enforcement. It is medically sound but implemented with Bolshevik thoroughness — armed cordons, forced delousing, confiscation of infected clothing. Effective but adding to the population's misery."},
        {text: "Organize a public campaign mobilizing party members for sanitation work — lead by example.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 15, survival: 0.8, response: "You organize communist subbotniki (voluntary work days) devoted to sanitation. Party members cleaning barracks and distributing soap makes powerful propaganda and actually helps. You gain a reputation as someone who rolls up their sleeves."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The nationalities question becomes urgent as the Red Army reconquers territories of the former Russian Empire. In Ukraine, competing factions — Bolsheviks, nationalists, anarchists under Makhno, and various warlords — make the situation chaotic. Stalin, as Commissar of Nationalities, is asserting central control. Ukrainian Bolsheviks demand genuine autonomy.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support Ukrainian Bolshevik autonomy — each nation must find its own path to socialism.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 0, reputation: 10, survival: 0.75, response: "You back Ukrainian self-governance within the revolution. Lenin sympathizes in principle but Stalin pushes for centralization. Your position wins friends among non-Russian Bolsheviks but makes powerful enemies in Moscow."},
        {text: "Back Stalin's centralist approach — a unified command is essential during the Civil War.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You support centralized control over Ukraine. Stalin appreciates the backing. The practical reality is that military necessity does demand coordination from Moscow. But 'temporary' wartime centralization has a way of becoming permanent."},
        {text: "Propose a temporary alliance with Makhno's anarchist forces against the Whites — deal with them later.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You advocate a tactical alliance with the anarchist Black Army. Such alliances are formed and broken repeatedly during the Civil War. The Bolsheviks will eventually crush Makhno, but his forces are useful against Denikin for now."},
        {text: "Focus on land reform in Ukraine — win the peasants over and the national question resolves itself.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You argue that class politics should take precedence over national politics. Distribute land to Ukrainian peasants and they will support the revolution regardless of what flag flies over Kyiv. A materialist analysis that Lenin would approve."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Denikin's White Army has pushed to within 200 miles of Moscow. Panic grips the capital. Some officials are already evacuating their families. Lenin orders all-out mobilization. Trotsky rushes to the Southern Front. The question of whether to defend Moscow or retreat to the Urals is debated. Every Bolshevik must demonstrate their commitment.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Volunteer immediately for the Southern Front — Moscow must be defended at all costs.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 0, reputation: 15, survival: 0.65, response: "You rush to the front. The danger is real — Denikin's Cossacks are formidable. But the Red Army counterattacks successfully, and those who fought in the darkest hour earn immense prestige. If you survive."},
        {text: "Organize the defense of Moscow itself — fortifications, worker militias, evacuation plans.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You throw yourself into rear-area defense preparations. Barricades, militia drilling, and contingency planning. The crisis passes when Denikin is pushed back, but your organizational work demonstrates calm competence under pressure."},
        {text: "Advocate a strategic retreat to the Urals if necessary — preserve the party leadership to fight another day.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 10, reputation: -10, survival: 0.8, response: "You propose contingency plans for retreat. Lenin has privately considered this, but publicly it sounds like defeatism. When Moscow holds, your suggestion is remembered as cowardice rather than prudence."},
        {text: "Use the crisis to root out 'defeatists' and 'panic-mongers' in the rear — tighten security.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You turn the military crisis into an internal security operation, hunting for spies and defeatists behind the lines. The Cheka appreciates your vigilance. Some of those you denounce are genuinely disloyal; others are merely frightened."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The party's organizational structure is being formalized. A new Orgburo (Organizational Bureau) and a restructured Secretariat are created to handle the growing administrative burden. These bodies will control party appointments, discipline, and communications. Stalin is appointed to the Orgburo. Most see this as tedious bureaucratic work. Where do you invest your time?",
      choices: [
        {text: "Seek appointment to the Orgburo — controlling party administration means controlling the party.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You recognize the importance of organizational power before most others do. Working alongside Stalin in the party apparatus, you build expertise in the machinery that will determine the succession struggle. Prescient."},
        {text: "Focus on military work — the Red Army is where glory and influence lie during the Civil War.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.8, response: "You follow the action to the front. Military heroes of the Civil War — Trotsky, Frunze, Tukhachevsky — command immense prestige. But military glory fades; bureaucratic power endures."},
        {text: "Concentrate on economic administration — someone must keep the factories running.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You take on the unglamorous work of managing industrial production under War Communism. The Supreme Council of National Economy needs competent administrators. Being indispensable has survival value."},
        {text: "Invest in propaganda and agitation work — shaping minds is as important as commanding armies.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You enter the world of Bolshevik propaganda — newspapers, posters, agitprop trains. Bukharin is already a major figure in this sphere. The ability to articulate the party line is always valued."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Reports from the front describe atrocities committed by both sides. White forces conduct pogroms against Jews, blaming them for Bolshevism. Red forces carry out reprisals against villages suspected of supporting the Whites. A delegation of Jewish Bundists approaches you seeking Bolshevik protection for Jewish communities caught between the armies.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Issue a strong condemnation of pogroms and order Red Army units to protect Jewish communities.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 15, survival: 0.85, response: "You take a principled stand against anti-Semitic violence. The Bolshevik opposition to pogroms is genuine and wins significant Jewish support for the revolution. Your moral leadership on this issue is remembered favorably."},
        {text: "Use the White pogroms as propaganda — proof that counter-revolution means barbarism.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You turn the White atrocities into powerful propaganda. Posters and leaflets documenting pogroms help recruit Jews and minorities to the Red cause. You serve both justice and political expediency simultaneously."},
        {text: "Warn the Bundists that their separate organization must merge into the Communist Party — no room for ethnic parties.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You offer protection but demand political absorption. The Bund must dissolve; its members may join the Communist Party individually. This reflects genuine Bolshevik policy — no separate ethnic organizations within the proletarian vanguard."},
        {text: "Quietly note that some Red Army units are also committing pogroms and demand internal discipline.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.8, response: "You acknowledge an uncomfortable truth — Budyonny's First Cavalry Army has been implicated in anti-Jewish violence. Raising this internally is necessary but sensitive. Trotsky, himself Jewish, supports your call for discipline."}
      ]
    }
  ],
  9: [
    {
      text: "The trade union debate has split the party into multiple factions. Trotsky demands the 'shaking up' and militarization of unions. The Workers' Opposition under Shliapnikov wants unions to manage the economy directly. Bukharin proposes his own compromise. Lenin's 'Platform of Ten' advocates unions as schools of communism. You must choose your platform before the Congress vote.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support Lenin's Platform of Ten — unions should educate workers, not command or be commanded.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.95, response: "You back Lenin's winning platform. It receives the majority of votes at the Congress. Siding with Lenin on the trade union question is both principled and politically astute — he has assembled the broadest coalition."},
        {text: "Back Trotsky's militarization — the economy needs the same iron discipline as the army.", loyalty: -5, cunning: -5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.75, response: "You support Trotsky's hard line. It appeals to those who value efficiency over democracy, but Lenin's coalition crushes it at the Congress. You have demonstrated loyalty to Trotsky at a moment when his star is waning."},
        {text: "Join the Workers' Opposition — genuine workers' democracy through trade union power.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -10, reputation: 15, survival: 0.6, response: "You align with Kollontai and Shliapnikov. The Workers' Opposition is the most democratic platform but the most politically dangerous. Lenin will soon push through a ban on factions, and your Opposition membership will become a liability."},
        {text: "Support Bukharin's buffer group — try to mediate between Lenin and Trotsky.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You join Bukharin's attempt at compromise. It fails to gain traction — in a factional fight, the middle ground is often the most vulnerable position. But you avoid the extremes and emerge without strong enemies."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "War Communism has created a black market economy. Private trade is officially illegal, but the 'bagmen' — small-scale traders carrying sacks of grain and goods between city and countryside — keep millions alive. The Cheka regularly arrests bagmen, but they are too numerous to suppress entirely. A proposal comes to crack down harder on illegal trade.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Crack down ruthlessly on the black market — illegal trade undermines state control of the economy.", loyalty: 10, cunning: -5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.8, response: "You support harsh enforcement. Roadblocks, confiscations, and arrests intensify. But the black market is the only functioning distribution system. Cracking down on it means more people starve. The policy is ideologically correct and practically disastrous."},
        {text: "Tolerate the bagmen quietly — arresting them serves no purpose when the state cannot provide alternatives.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You argue for pragmatic tolerance. Lenin is privately sympathetic — he knows War Communism is failing. Your position foreshadows the NEP that will be introduced at the next Congress. Being early with the right idea is better than being late."},
        {text: "Propose legalizing small-scale trade to bring the black market under state regulation.", loyalty: -10, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.7, response: "You effectively propose the NEP a year early. The party is not ready for this ideological retreat. You are accused of wanting to restore capitalism. But within a year, Lenin himself will propose essentially the same thing."},
        {text: "Focus enforcement on large-scale speculators while ignoring small bagmen — target the profiteers, not the desperate.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You propose a differentiated approach: crush organized black marketeers and speculators while turning a blind eye to the subsistence-level bagmen. This pragmatic middle ground is quietly adopted in many localities."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Polish-Soviet War has ended in defeat at the Battle of Warsaw. Tukhachevsky's armies were routed. The dream of carrying revolution to Europe on bayonet points has died. Recriminations fly — who is responsible for the disaster? Stalin, who commanded the Southern Front, refused to redirect his forces to support Tukhachevsky's drive on Warsaw. Trotsky blames the political leadership for the entire adventure.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Blame the military leadership for the defeat — Tukhachevsky overextended the lines.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You pin blame on military overreach rather than political decisions. This protects both Lenin (who supported the campaign) and Stalin (who disobeyed orders). A safely distributed blame that offends no senior figure."},
        {text: "Point to Stalin's refusal to cooperate with Tukhachevsky as a key factor in the defeat.", loyalty: -5, cunning: -5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.7, response: "You identify Stalin's insubordination as a cause of the Warsaw disaster. This is historically accurate — Stalin's forces were diverted to capture Lvov instead of supporting the main thrust. But accusing Stalin openly is storing up trouble."},
        {text: "Argue the entire campaign was misconceived — you cannot export revolution by military force.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.8, response: "You question the fundamental premise of the Polish campaign. Polish workers did not rally to the Red Army; they rallied to defend their new nation. This honest assessment irritates Lenin but demonstrates strategic clarity."},
        {text: "Call for learning military lessons from the defeat and strengthening the Red Army for future campaigns.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You redirect the discussion from blame to improvement. Studying the defeat, reforming tactics, and modernizing the army are constructive responses. Tukhachevsky himself will lead military reforms based on the Polish experience."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Labor militarization is implemented under Trotsky's direction. Workers are organized into 'labor armies' and assigned to economic reconstruction with military discipline. Absenteeism is punished. Workers cannot change jobs without permission. Productivity remains low despite coercion. A heated debate erupts about whether workers can be motivated by force alone.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support labor militarization fully — the country is in ruins and discipline is the only path to recovery.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 0, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You back Trotsky's system. The labor armies rebuild some infrastructure and clear wartime damage. But forced labor is deeply unpopular and inefficient. The policy will be quietly abandoned when the NEP arrives."},
        {text: "Argue for material incentives instead — pay workers more for greater productivity.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.8, response: "You propose what amounts to wage differentials and bonus systems. This 'bourgeois' approach is ideologically suspect under War Communism, but it works. Lenin is increasingly receptive to practical solutions over ideological purity."},
        {text: "Propose 'communist Saturdays' — voluntary work days to inspire workers through revolutionary enthusiasm.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.9, response: "You champion the subbotnik movement. Lenin himself participates in a famous communist Saturday, carrying a log. The voluntary approach generates propaganda value and some genuine productivity. It is the humane face of socialist construction."},
        {text: "Quietly redirect labor army units under your authority to projects that benefit your political base.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You use the labor armies to build infrastructure in areas that strengthen your personal position. A road here, a rebuilt factory there — creating patronage networks while fulfilling plan targets. The Soviet system rewards those who play the game."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Democratic Centralist faction raises the alarm about growing bureaucratization. The party apparatus is swelling — thousands of officials now control local party organizations, often without input from ordinary members. Party meetings are stage-managed. Dissent is stifled. Sapronov and Osinsky warn that the revolution is creating a new ruling class of bureaucrats.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Dismiss the Democratic Centralists — bureaucratic organization is necessary to govern a vast country.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You defend the growing apparatus. Lenin agrees that organization is essential, though he shares some concerns about bureaucratism. Your defense of the status quo pleases those who benefit from it — which is most of the leadership."},
        {text: "Acknowledge the bureaucratization problem but argue it can be solved through better training and rotation of cadres.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You take a reformist position — the bureaucracy needs improvement, not abolition. This moderate stance avoids offending either the apparatus or the critics. Proposing solutions rather than just criticisms marks you as constructive."},
        {text: "Support the Democratic Centralists' demands for genuine internal party elections and open debate.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -10, reputation: 15, survival: 0.6, response: "You call for real democracy within the party. The faction ban that will come at the 10th Congress next year will make this position formally illegal. You have placed yourself on the wrong side of the coming crackdown on dissent."},
        {text: "Propose a party purge to remove careerists and 'dead wood' from the apparatus.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You suggest cleaning the party of those who joined for personal advantage rather than conviction. A purge of membership rolls is indeed conducted in 1921. Your proposal shows vigilance against corruption while strengthening the apparatus's control."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Congress debates economic policy as War Communism shows signs of total failure. Industrial production has fallen to a fraction of pre-war levels. The currency is worthless. Barter has replaced money in much of the country. Some voices timidly suggest limited concessions to private trade. Trotsky himself has privately proposed something resembling what will become the NEP.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Defend War Communism as a temporary but necessary system — it won the Civil War.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 0, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You defend the existing system. War Communism did provide the centralized resource extraction needed to fight the Whites. But the war is ending, and clinging to wartime measures in peacetime will provoke rebellion. Kronstadt is months away."},
        {text: "Cautiously suggest that some economic liberalization may be needed now that the military emergency is passing.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You test the waters with careful suggestions about loosening economic controls. You are not alone — Lenin is privately reconsidering the entire approach. Your timing is good, just ahead of the curve."},
        {text: "Argue that the problem is not War Communism itself but insufficient planning — we need better central coordination.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You argue for improving the system rather than abandoning it. More sophisticated planning, better coordination between sectors. This technocratic optimism will persist throughout Soviet history — the belief that better management can fix structural problems."},
        {text: "Propose a pilot program of limited free trade in one province as an experiment.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You suggest a controlled experiment before committing to systemic change. This scientific approach to policy appeals to Lenin's empirical instincts. The NEP will essentially be this experiment scaled nationwide."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "A controversy erupts over the fate of the Cossack communities. During the Civil War, many Cossack regions supported the Whites. The policy of 'decossackization' — breaking up Cossack settlements, confiscating land, and mass deportation — has been implemented with extreme violence. Some party members protest the collective punishment of entire communities.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support decossackization — the Cossacks were the Tsar's shock troops and class enemies of the revolution.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 0, reputation: -10, survival: 0.85, response: "You back the harsh policy. Cossack communities are broken up, their privileges abolished, their land redistributed. The policy is effective in destroying a military threat but creates lasting bitterness that will resurface during collectivization."},
        {text: "Argue for distinguishing between wealthy Cossack officers and poor Cossack farmers.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.85, response: "You apply class analysis to the Cossack question — punish the atamans and officers but win over the poor Cossacks. This is the theoretically correct Marxist approach and finds support among those uncomfortable with collective punishment."},
        {text: "Propose resettlement programs to integrate former Cossacks into collective farming communities.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You suggest a constructive alternative to pure repression. Resettle and re-educate rather than simply punish. The proposal is partially adopted, though in practice resettlement often means forced displacement."},
        {text: "Stay silent on the Cossack question — it is a military matter best left to the Revolutionary Military Council.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You decline to take a position on this bloody topic. The Cossack question is entangled with military operations and regional politics. Avoiding it entirely is the safest course — no one is punished for not having an opinion on Cossack policy."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "As the Civil War winds down, captured White officers and soldiers must be dealt with. Some advocate mass executions or permanent imprisonment. Others argue that amnesty for rank-and-file soldiers and technical experts would help rebuild the country. Thousands of former White officers possess military and engineering skills the Soviet state desperately needs.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Execute the officers and imprison the rest — they fought against the revolution and must pay.", loyalty: 5, cunning: -5, reputation: -10, survival: 0.8, response: "You demand maximum punishment. Some officers are indeed executed, but the policy is not universally applied — the state needs skilled personnel too badly. Your bloodthirstiness earns approval from hardliners but does not become general policy."},
        {text: "Offer amnesty to those willing to serve the Soviet state — we need their skills.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You advocate pragmatic amnesty. Many former White officers do serve the Soviet state — some brilliantly, like Shaposhnikov who becomes a key military planner. Your pragmatism aligns with Lenin's policy of utilizing bourgeois specialists."},
        {text: "Propose screening commissions to evaluate each case individually — punish the war criminals, recruit the useful.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You suggest a systematic approach. Screening commissions are established to sort prisoners into categories. This bureaucratic solution satisfies both the desire for justice and the need for expertise. A characteristically Soviet compromise."},
        {text: "Use the captured officers as leverage — offer amnesty in exchange for intelligence about remaining White networks.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You see intelligence value in the prisoners. By offering amnesty for information, you help the Cheka map and destroy remaining counter-revolutionary networks. The security services appreciate your strategic thinking."}
      ]
    }
  ],
  10: [
    {
      text: "The Kronstadt sailors — once hailed as the revolution's vanguard — have revolted, demanding free soviets, freedom of speech for socialist parties, and an end to War Communism. Trotsky calls them counter-revolutionaries. Tukhachevsky is ordered to storm the fortress across the ice. Some party members are deeply troubled by the order to fire on the revolution's own heroes. The assault must happen before the spring thaw.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support the assault without reservation — Kronstadt has become a counter-revolutionary base regardless of who the sailors once were.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You back the bloody assault. Tukhachevsky's forces storm across the frozen Gulf of Finland. Thousands die on both sides. The revolt is crushed. You have demonstrated the ruthlessness the leadership demands."},
        {text: "Volunteer to negotiate with the sailors before the assault — perhaps bloodshed can be avoided.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 0, reputation: 15, survival: 0.65, response: "You offer to mediate. The leadership rejects negotiation — it would legitimize the revolt. Your humanitarian instinct is seen as political naivety. The assault proceeds without your input, and your attempted mediation is noted as wavering."},
        {text: "Support the assault but argue that the sailors' economic grievances should be addressed through policy reform.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You take the nuanced position: crush the revolt militarily but address its root causes politically. This is essentially Lenin's own approach — he introduces the NEP at this very Congress while ordering the Kronstadt assault. You have read the leader perfectly."},
        {text: "Argue that Kronstadt proves War Communism must end immediately — the sailors speak for the people.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.6, response: "You defend the sailors' grievances. This is political poison — at the Congress, Lenin uses Kronstadt to demand unity and crush dissent. Those who sympathize with the rebels are suspected of disloyalty to the party."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Lenin proposes the New Economic Policy — replacing grain requisitioning with a tax in kind, legalizing private trade, and allowing small private enterprises. Old Bolsheviks are stunned. After years of War Communism, this feels like a retreat to capitalism. Lenin calls it 'one step back to take two steps forward.' Many delegates struggle with the ideological implications.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Embrace the NEP enthusiastically — Lenin's genius is in knowing when to retreat strategically.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.95, response: "You praise the NEP as tactical brilliance. The peasants will produce more grain willingly than they ever did under forced requisitioning. Your economic pragmatism mirrors Lenin's own. This is the winning position."},
        {text: "Accept the NEP reluctantly — it is necessary but temporary, and we must be vigilant against capitalist restoration.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You vote for the NEP while expressing ideological reservations. This is the position of many honest Bolsheviks. Your caution is noted but not penalized — Lenin himself calls the NEP a retreat, after all."},
        {text: "Oppose the NEP — it betrays everything the Civil War was fought for.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.6, response: "You speak against the NEP from the left. You are not alone — many Civil War veterans feel the same. But Lenin's authority carries the day, and opposing him on a major policy initiative is dangerous."},
        {text: "Focus on the practical details of implementing the tax in kind — make yourself the expert on the transition.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.95, response: "You skip the ideological debate and master the technical details of transitioning from requisitioning to taxation. The party desperately needs people who can make the NEP work in practice. You become indispensable."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Lenin proposes a ban on factions within the party, including a secret clause allowing the Central Committee to expel members who form organized groups. The Workers' Opposition and Democratic Centralists protest that this will kill internal democracy. Lenin argues that with enemies on all sides and Kronstadt fresh in memory, the party cannot afford organized dissent.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support the faction ban completely — party unity is the revolution's greatest weapon.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.95, response: "You back the ban on factions. It passes with a large majority. This resolution will become the most powerful weapon in Soviet political history — any organized opposition within the party can now be declared illegal. You helped forge the tool that Stalin will later wield with devastating effect."},
        {text: "Vote for the ban but oppose the secret clause on expulsion — that gives the Central Committee too much power.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You support the principle but resist the enforcement mechanism. The secret clause passes anyway. Your nuanced opposition is too subtle to be remembered as either heroic dissent or dangerous disloyalty."},
        {text: "Oppose the faction ban — it will destroy the party's ability to correct mistakes through open debate.", loyalty: -15, cunning: -10, reputation: 15, survival: 0.5, response: "You prophetically warn that banning organized dissent will lead to one-person dictatorship. History will vindicate you completely. But the delegates are frightened by Kronstadt and foreign intervention — they vote overwhelmingly for the ban. Your opposition is recorded."},
        {text: "Abstain from the vote — you see the logic but cannot bring yourself to support silencing comrades.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.75, response: "You sit on your hands. The abstention is noted. It is a coward's compromise — refusing to take a stand while the party's future is being decided. But at least you did not vote to silence your fellow revolutionaries."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Workers' Opposition, led by Alexandra Kollontai and Alexander Shliapnikov, presents a platform demanding that trade unions manage the entire national economy and that workers have direct control over production. Kollontai's pamphlet circulates widely. Lenin denounces the group as an 'anarcho-syndicalist deviation.' Under the new faction ban, their very existence is technically illegal.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Denounce the Workers' Opposition as objectively counter-revolutionary — they are splitting the party during a crisis.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You attack the Workers' Opposition harshly. Shliapnikov, a genuine proletarian and Old Bolshevik, is stung by the accusation. But the leadership rewards your combativeness. The Workers' Opposition is marginalized."},
        {text: "Express sympathy with their ideals while arguing their methods are wrong — workers' control must come gradually.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You acknowledge the Workers' Opposition's sincerity while disagreeing with their program. This diplomatic approach keeps you on speaking terms with both sides. In Soviet politics, maintaining relationships across factional lines is invaluable insurance."},
        {text: "Secretly circulate Kollontai's pamphlet — the workers deserve to hear these arguments.", loyalty: -15, cunning: -10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.5, response: "You distribute banned material. If caught, this violates the newly passed faction ban. Kollontai's ideas about workers' democracy and sexual liberation are among the most radical in the party. Supporting her is principled and extremely risky."},
        {text: "Propose that some Workers' Opposition members be given responsible economic posts to channel their energy constructively.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You suggest co-opting the opposition rather than crushing it. Give Shliapnikov and others real work managing industries and their oppositional energy will dissipate. Lenin appreciates this shrewd approach to neutralizing dissent."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The famine of 1921-22 devastates the Volga region, the Urals, and Ukraine. Millions are starving. Reports of cannibalism emerge. The American Relief Administration under Herbert Hoover offers massive humanitarian aid. Patriarch Tikhon of the Orthodox Church also mobilizes relief, giving the Church renewed moral authority. Lenin orders the confiscation of church valuables to fund famine relief — and to break the Church's influence.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Enthusiastically support seizing church valuables — use the famine to destroy organized religion.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -10, survival: 0.9, response: "You back Lenin's campaign with gusto. Church gold and silver are confiscated across the country. Priests who resist are arrested or shot. Lenin's secret directive calls for using the famine as a pretext to strike a blow against the Church from which it will never recover."},
        {text: "Support confiscation but argue it should be done diplomatically to avoid provoking religious unrest.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You advocate a less confrontational approach. In some regions, church leaders voluntarily surrender valuables when approached respectfully. Your moderate methods work better than brute force and avoid creating martyrs."},
        {text: "Focus on organizing direct famine relief — distributing food matters more than seizing church gold.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 15, survival: 0.8, response: "You throw yourself into humanitarian work. Organizing food distribution, cooperating with the ARA, setting up feeding stations. Your focus on saving lives rather than political maneuvering earns genuine gratitude from the starving population."},
        {text: "Argue that accepting American aid is humiliating but seizing Russian church property is even worse — fund relief through other means.", loyalty: -5, cunning: -5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.7, response: "You oppose both foreign dependency and anti-Church campaigns. This principled but impractical stance satisfies no one. The famine requires immediate action from every available source, and your objections delay relief."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The party membership purge of 1921 is underway. Hundreds of thousands who joined during the Civil War are being reviewed. Many are 'careerists' who joined when it became advantageous, not out of conviction. You are appointed to a local purge commission. Your decisions will determine who keeps their party card — and their career.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Be ruthless — expel anyone who cannot demonstrate genuine proletarian credentials and revolutionary commitment.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You conduct a thorough purge, expelling a third of your district's membership. Some deserving members are caught in the net. The party apparatus appreciates your thoroughness — a lean, disciplined party is more controllable."},
        {text: "Be fair — evaluate each case individually and give borderline members a chance to prove themselves.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.85, response: "You conduct careful, individualized reviews. Your purge commission is slower but more just than others. Those you spare remember your fairness. Those you expel at least felt they received a hearing."},
        {text: "Use the purge to remove your political rivals while protecting your allies regardless of their credentials.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: -10, survival: 0.85, response: "You weaponize the purge for personal advantage. Political enemies lose their party cards on technicalities; allies are waved through. This cynical manipulation of the purge process is common but creates dangerous resentments among those you targeted."},
        {text: "Focus on removing corrupt members who have used their party cards for personal enrichment.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.9, response: "You target corruption specifically. NEPmen with party connections, officials who have enriched themselves through their positions. This anti-corruption focus is popular with ordinary members and aligns with the purge's stated purpose."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Grain requisitioning is being replaced by the tax in kind under the NEP, but implementation is chaotic. Local officials accustomed to seizing grain at gunpoint struggle to transition to a tax-based system. Peasants remain suspicious that the tax is just requisitioning under a new name. You are sent to a rural province to oversee the transition.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Implement the new tax system strictly by the book — show the peasants that the party keeps its word.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.85, response: "You enforce the tax honestly, taking only what is legally owed. Peasant trust slowly builds. Grain deliveries actually increase as farmers are motivated to produce surplus they can sell freely. The NEP begins to work."},
        {text: "Set the tax rates high enough to extract maximum grain while technically following the new law.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You push the tax to its upper limits. More grain flows to the cities, but peasants feel cheated — the new system feels like the old one with legal paperwork. Your district meets its quotas, which is what Moscow measures."},
        {text: "Recruit local peasant leaders as allies — let them help set fair tax rates for their communities.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.8, response: "You involve village elders and local leaders in the process. This bottom-up approach builds genuine cooperation but makes hardliners in the party nervous. Sharing power with peasants, even informally, smells of political deviation."},
        {text: "Report back that the old requisitioning system worked better and the NEP is causing confusion in the countryside.", loyalty: -5, cunning: -10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.65, response: "You criticize the NEP's rural implementation. Lenin is committed to this policy, and questioning it so soon after adoption suggests you are either opposed to the reform or incompetent at implementing it. Neither interpretation helps you."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "At the margins of the Congress, delegates discuss the party's relationship with other socialist parties. The Mensheviks and SRs are being systematically repressed — their leaders arrested or driven into exile. Some Old Bolsheviks who remember fighting alongside Mensheviks in the underground feel uneasy. A prominent Menshevik leader sends a letter from prison appealing for mercy.",
      choices: [
        {text: "The Mensheviks chose counter-revolution — they deserve no mercy from the revolutionary state.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You declare the Mensheviks irredeemable enemies. The GPU (successor to the Cheka) continues its work of suppressing the last remnants of non-Bolshevik socialism. Your hardline position earns approval from the security apparatus."},
        {text: "Propose that individual Mensheviks who renounce their past be allowed to join the Communist Party.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You advocate absorption rather than destruction. Allow former Mensheviks to recant and join the party. This is pragmatic — some possess valuable expertise. The party does quietly accept some former Mensheviks, though their past remains a vulnerability."},
        {text: "Argue privately that jailing fellow socialists contradicts everything the revolution stands for.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.65, response: "You express moral qualms about persecuting other socialists. This is a dangerous position — the party line holds that only one party can represent the proletariat. Sympathy for Mensheviks is treated as evidence of ideological unreliability."},
        {text: "Ignore the Menshevik question entirely — focus on building the Communist Party rather than worrying about its rivals.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You decline to engage with the question. The Mensheviks are a spent force; worrying about them is backward-looking. Your focus on constructive party-building rather than repression marks you as forward-thinking."}
      ]
    }
  ],
  11: [
    {
      text: "Lenin has suffered his first stroke in May 1922, temporarily losing the ability to speak and write. He partially recovers but is clearly diminished. The question of who governs during his incapacity is delicate — no formal succession mechanism exists. Stalin, Kamenev, and Zinoviev quietly begin coordinating policy. Trotsky stands aloof. You receive a private request from Krupskaya asking you to visit Lenin.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Visit Lenin and report honestly on party affairs — he deserves to know what is happening.", loyalty: 5, cunning: -5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.75, response: "You visit the ailing leader. Lenin is grateful for honest information. But Stalin controls access to Lenin, and your unauthorized visit is reported. Stalin begins to view you as someone who might carry messages from Lenin that he cannot control."},
        {text: "Decline the visit — Lenin's doctors have restricted visitors and you respect their authority.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You defer to the official medical restrictions — which Stalin has helped establish to isolate Lenin. Your discretion is rewarded. In the succession struggle, those who stayed away from the sickbed avoided entanglement in dangerous intrigues."},
        {text: "Visit Lenin but report the conversation to Stalin afterward — demonstrate loyalty to the emerging leadership.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -10, survival: 0.9, response: "You see Lenin and then brief Stalin on what was discussed. This double game earns Stalin's trust. He appreciates having informants around the ailing leader. But if Lenin discovers your betrayal, the consequences could be severe."},
        {text: "Use the visit to gauge Lenin's mental state — knowledge of his true condition is politically valuable.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You assess Lenin clinically. How lucid is he? Can he still influence events? This intelligence helps you calibrate your own political positioning. Information about the leader's health is the most valuable currency in a succession crisis."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The NEP is producing tangible results. Private traders — the 'NEPmen' — are thriving. Restaurants, shops, and small factories reopen. But the contrast between NEPmen's prosperity and workers' poverty creates resentment. The party debates whether to restrict NEPmen or let the market work. Cultural life is also flourishing with relative artistic freedom.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Defend the NEP vigorously — economic recovery proves the policy is correct, regardless of who profits.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You become a vocal NEP defender. The economy is growing, famine is receding, and the state is collecting revenue through taxation of private trade. Lenin's pragmatic retreat is working. Your pro-NEP position aligns with the leadership consensus."},
        {text: "Argue for higher taxes on NEPmen to redistribute their profits to workers.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.9, response: "You propose using the tax system to address inequality while preserving market incentives. This balanced approach satisfies both those who want the NEP to continue and those troubled by the emergence of a new bourgeoisie."},
        {text: "Warn that the NEP is creating a new bourgeoisie that will eventually demand political power — we are nurturing our own gravediggers.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You echo concerns that private capital will seek political representation. This leftist critique has theoretical merit but runs counter to Lenin's policy. You are not yet labeled an oppositionist, but your skepticism is noted."},
        {text: "Focus on using NEP revenues to fund state industry — let the NEPmen generate the capital for socialist construction.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.95, response: "You propose channeling NEP-generated wealth into state-owned heavy industry. This synthesis of market economics and socialist planning anticipates the debates that will dominate the rest of the decade. A far-sighted and politically safe position."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Stalin has been appointed General Secretary, a position most regard as purely administrative. But Stalin uses it to control party appointments across the entire country — placing allies in key positions and transferring opponents to remote postings. A few perceptive observers, including Lenin, begin to worry about the concentration of organizational power.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Offer to assist Stalin with the appointment process — make yourself useful to the organizational machinery.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: -5, survival: 0.95, response: "You attach yourself to Stalin's personnel operation. Helping decide who gets posted where gives you both influence and intelligence. Those who recognized the power of the Secretariat early were rewarded with decades of career security."},
        {text: "Raise concerns about the growing power of the Secretariat at the Congress — no single organ should control all appointments.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.65, response: "You flag the danger of concentrated organizational power. Lenin privately agrees — he will soon dictate notes criticizing Stalin's accumulation of authority. But publicly challenging the General Secretary's prerogatives makes you an immediate target."},
        {text: "Request a posting to an important provincial position — build your own power base away from Moscow intrigues.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You seek a strong regional posting. Running a major province or republic gives you independent authority and a political base. Many future Soviet leaders — including Khrushchev — built their careers through regional power."},
        {text: "Focus on your own policy area and avoid the organizational politics entirely.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You keep your head down and focus on substantive work. The organizational machinations happening around you will determine the fate of the revolution, but not everyone needs to be involved. Sometimes the best strategy is productive obscurity."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The party's relationship with the intelligentsia is in flux. Lenin orders the deportation of over 200 intellectuals — philosophers, economists, historians — on the so-called 'Philosophy Steamer.' They are exiled rather than imprisoned, but the message is clear: independent thought outside party control will not be tolerated. Some party members with intellectual backgrounds are uncomfortable.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support the deportations — bourgeois intellectuals are a fifth column who undermine socialist construction.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You approve the deportation of 'ideological saboteurs.' Lenin considers the intellectuals more dangerous than armed counter-revolutionaries because they poison minds. Your support for the cultural purge demonstrates ideological reliability."},
        {text: "Argue that deportation is actually merciful — in other revolutionary situations, intellectuals were simply shot.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You frame the deportations as humanitarian by revolutionary standards. Exile to Berlin is better than a Cheka basement. This darkly pragmatic perspective acknowledges the regime's violence while appearing moderate within it."},
        {text: "Suggest that some intellectuals could be won over through re-education rather than expelled wholesale.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You advocate for rehabilitation over expulsion. Some intellectuals might be converted to Marxism through proper education. This position reflects a belief in persuasion that the party is increasingly abandoning in favor of coercion."},
        {text: "Propose replacing the deported intellectuals with newly trained 'Red professors' from proletarian backgrounds.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You call for building a new socialist intelligentsia. Worker-faculty programs, communist universities, and party schools will produce a generation of ideologically reliable experts. This constructive approach to the brain drain wins broad approval."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "A delegation from Georgia arrives at the Congress with explosive grievances. Stalin and his deputy Ordzhonikidze have been forcing Georgian Bolsheviks into a Transcaucasian Federation against their wishes. Ordzhonikidze physically struck a Georgian Communist who protested. Lenin, from his sickbed, is gathering evidence against Stalin's handling of the Georgian question. The issue threatens to blow open.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Side with the Georgian Bolsheviks — their right to autonomy should be respected.", loyalty: -5, cunning: -10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.6, response: "You back the Georgian cause. Lenin would approve, but Lenin is incapacitated and unable to act. Stalin views any support for the Georgians as a personal attack. Without Lenin's protection, Georgian sympathizers are exposed."},
        {text: "Support the Transcaucasian Federation — centralization strengthens the Soviet state.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You defend the federation plan. Stalin rewards loyalty on this issue, which he treats as a test of personal allegiance. The Georgians are overruled. Mdivani and other Georgian oppositionists are gradually demoted."},
        {text: "Call for an investigation into Ordzhonikidze's conduct — violence against a comrade is unacceptable regardless of the policy question.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.75, response: "You focus on the personal violence rather than the policy debate. This is a shrewd distinction — condemning Ordzhonikidze's behavior without necessarily opposing the federation. But Stalin protects his lieutenants fiercely."},
        {text: "Propose that the Congress form a commission to study the Georgian question — delay the decision.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You kick the issue to a commission, buying time. Commissions are the Soviet system's way of burying controversial questions. By the time the commission reports, Lenin's declining health will have removed the issue's most powerful champion."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Congress debates the formation of the USSR. The choice is between Stalin's 'autonomization' plan — where non-Russian republics would be absorbed into the Russian Federation — and Lenin's proposal for a voluntary union of equal Soviet republics. The Union of Soviet Socialist Republics is officially proclaimed in December 1922. The structure will determine center-periphery relations for decades.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support Lenin's model of a voluntary union of equal republics — this will win the non-Russian peoples to socialism.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.85, response: "You back Lenin's more generous federalist model. It is adopted, at least on paper. In practice, the center will dominate the periphery regardless of formal structures. But supporting Lenin's position is both principled and politically safe."},
        {text: "Back Stalin's autonomization plan — administrative efficiency requires centralized control.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You support Stalin's preferred model. Lenin's intervention forces Stalin to retreat, but Stalin remembers who supported his original plan. The tension between formal federalism and actual centralism will define Soviet governance."},
        {text: "Propose strong central control over military and foreign policy while granting genuine cultural and economic autonomy to republics.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You craft a sophisticated middle position: federal structure with centralized security but genuine local autonomy in cultural affairs. This mirrors the actual compromise that emerges. Your detailed proposals demonstrate policy expertise."},
        {text: "Argue that the national question is secondary to class struggle — workers of all nationalities share the same interests.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 0, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You take the orthodox Marxist line that class transcends nation. This is theoretically correct but practically naive — national sentiments remain powerful throughout the Soviet period. Lenin himself insists that Great Russian chauvinism must be actively combated."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Party membership has grown enormously but so has corruption. Officials use their positions for personal enrichment, taking bribes and granting favors. The 'NEP culture' of commerce and entertainment contrasts sharply with revolutionary austerity. Some members are caught frequenting nightclubs and casinos alongside NEPmen. A proposal for a new party purge targeting moral corruption is debated.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Demand a thorough purge of morally compromised members — Bolsheviks must live by a higher standard.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.85, response: "You call for moral renewal within the party. The purge commissions review members' personal conduct alongside their political reliability. Your advocacy for revolutionary purity wins approval from ascetic Old Bolsheviks who despise the NEP's decadence."},
        {text: "Focus the purge on genuine corruption — embezzlement and bribery — rather than personal morality.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You distinguish between criminal corruption and personal lifestyle choices. Going after bribes and embezzlement is productive; policing members' private lives is intrusive and alienating. Your measured approach wins support from pragmatists."},
        {text: "Use the purge commission to target members allied with your political rivals.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: -10, survival: 0.85, response: "You exploit the purge for factional advantage. Everyone has some vulnerability — a questionable association, an unexplained absence, a bourgeois family member. The purge mechanism is easily weaponized by those who control it."},
        {text: "Argue that corruption is an inevitable consequence of the NEP and will diminish as socialism advances — no purge needed.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 0, survival: 0.8, response: "You take the long view, arguing that corruption is a symptom of the transitional period. As the socialist economy matures, material temptations will diminish. This theoretical optimism does not address the immediate problem."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Foreign policy is at a crossroads. The Soviet Union has signed the Treaty of Rapallo with Weimar Germany, breaking out of diplomatic isolation. Secret military cooperation with Germany includes training and weapons development that circumvent the Treaty of Versailles. The Comintern simultaneously promotes revolution in Germany. You are involved in discussions about the contradictions of dealing with a bourgeois state while trying to overthrow it.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Prioritize state-to-state relations with Germany — Rapallo gives us military and economic benefits we desperately need.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You advocate for realpolitik. The German military cooperation — secret tank and aircraft testing grounds on Soviet soil — provides technology the Red Army needs. Diplomacy must trump revolutionary rhetoric when survival is at stake."},
        {text: "Push for intensifying Comintern support for the German Communist Party — revolution in Germany would change everything.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 0, reputation: 10, survival: 0.8, response: "You prioritize world revolution over diplomatic niceties. The German revolution of 1923 will fail, vindicating the pragmatists. But the dream of a communist Germany remains powerful within the party."},
        {text: "Argue that we can pursue both tracks simultaneously — diplomacy and revolution are complementary tools.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You propose maintaining both channels. Soviet diplomats negotiate trade deals while Comintern agents prepare revolution. This dual-track approach is the actual Soviet practice. Your ability to hold contradictions comfortably is a valuable Soviet skill."},
        {text: "Warn that secret military cooperation with Germany will be exploited by our enemies if exposed.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You flag the security risks of the Rapallo arrangement. If the secret military programs leak, both governments face scandal. Your caution is sensible but unpopular — the leadership has decided the benefits outweigh the risks."}
      ]
    }
  ],
  12: [
    {
      text: "Lenin has suffered additional strokes and is now effectively incapacitated, able to communicate only with great difficulty. He has dictated a Testament critical of all major leaders, with a postscript calling for Stalin's removal as General Secretary. The triumvirate of Stalin, Zinoviev, and Kamenev has formed to block Trotsky from succeeding Lenin. You learn of the Testament's contents through a confidential source.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Keep the information to yourself — knowledge of the Testament is a dangerous asset to hold quietly.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You say nothing, storing this explosive knowledge for future use. The Testament will be read at a closed session after Lenin's death, but its suppression is being arranged. Knowing what Lenin thinks without acting on it is the quintessence of Soviet political survival."},
        {text: "Quietly inform Trotsky that Lenin supports removing Stalin — urge him to act before it is too late.", loyalty: -10, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.6, response: "You approach Trotsky with intelligence that should galvanize him into action. But Trotsky, characteristically, hesitates and philosophizes rather than fighting. His passivity in the face of Stalin's maneuvering will prove fatal to his political career."},
        {text: "Share the information with Stalin, demonstrating your loyalty to the emerging leader.", loyalty: 15, cunning: 10, reputation: -10, survival: 0.9, response: "You bring the Testament's contents to Stalin. He already knows, of course, but your willingness to betray the confidence proves your loyalty. Stalin rewards those who choose him over Lenin's dying wishes. A cold calculation, but an effective one."},
        {text: "Advocate publicly that all of Lenin's recent writings should be published in full — without specifying what they contain.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.7, response: "You call for transparency about Lenin's final views without revealing you know their content. This principled-seeming position threatens the triumvirate's plans. If pressed, you can claim you did not know what Lenin wrote — only that it should be public."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Scissors Crisis is devastating the smychka — the alliance between workers and peasants that underpins the NEP. Industrial goods cost far too much for peasants to buy, while agricultural prices are so low that farmers cannot afford to sell. Trotsky warns that without state planning to close the price gap, the whole NEP edifice will collapse. The triumvirate dismisses his analysis as opposition fearmongering.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Back the triumvirate — the market will self-correct and Trotsky is just looking for excuses to centralize power.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You dismiss the Scissors Crisis as temporary. The triumvirate appreciates your loyalty. The crisis does eventually ease, partly through policy adjustments the leadership implements while claiming the market corrected itself."},
        {text: "Support Trotsky's call for state planning — the data clearly shows market mechanisms alone cannot solve this.", loyalty: -10, cunning: 0, reputation: 10, survival: 0.6, response: "You side with Trotsky's economic analysis. It is correct — the Scissors Crisis requires state intervention. But supporting Trotsky on anything, no matter how rational, marks you as opposition. The political cost outweighs the intellectual satisfaction."},
        {text: "Propose specific technocratic measures — price controls, credit policy, industrial reform — without endorsing either faction.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 10, survival: 0.9, response: "You bypass the factional fight entirely, offering concrete policy solutions. Reduce industrial costs through efficiency drives. Extend agricultural credit. Your technocratic approach is adopted piecemeal by both sides while you avoid political contamination."},
        {text: "Argue that the Scissors Crisis proves the NEP was always a temporary retreat — it is time to return to socialist economic principles.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 0, reputation: 5, survival: 0.75, response: "You advocate ending the NEP and returning to centralized economics. This ultra-left position has few supporters in 1923. Stalin himself will eventually adopt this stance, but not for another five years. Your timing is poor."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Stalin's control of the party apparatus is becoming unmistakable. Through the Orgburo and Secretariat, he has placed loyalists in key positions across the country. The Central Committee is increasingly filled with people who owe their careers to Stalin. Trotsky calls this 'the bureaucratic degeneration of the revolution.' A group of 46 prominent party members signs a declaration protesting the lack of internal democracy.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Sign the Declaration of the 46 — internal party democracy must be defended.", loyalty: -15, cunning: -10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.5, response: "You add your name to the declaration. The 46 signatories include prominent Bolsheviks like Preobrazhensky, Pyatakov, and Antonov-Ovseenko. But signing is an act of open opposition to the triumvirate. Each signatory will eventually face consequences."},
        {text: "Refuse to sign but privately express agreement with the declaration's concerns.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You sympathize privately but keep your name off the document. This allows you to maintain relationships with the signatories without incurring the leadership's wrath. A coward's wisdom — but wisdom nonetheless."},
        {text: "Publicly denounce the Declaration of the 46 as a factional maneuver that violates the ban on organized opposition.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You attack the declaration as illegal factionalism under the 10th Congress ban. The triumvirate orchestrates a campaign against the 46. Your denunciation is one of many, but it marks you as reliably on the apparatus side."},
        {text: "Propose reforms to the appointment system that address the declaration's concerns without endorsing its authors.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You acknowledge the problem while rejecting the opposition's method. By proposing your own reforms to the party's organizational procedures, you appear responsive to legitimate concerns without aligning with the dissidents. Masterful positioning."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Georgian Affair reaches its climax at the Congress. Lenin had dictated a furious letter condemning Stalin and Ordzhonikidze's treatment of Georgian Communists, calling Stalin's behavior 'Great Russian bullying.' Lenin wanted Trotsky to present the Georgian case at the Congress, but Trotsky declined. Now the triumvirate is suppressing Lenin's notes. The Georgian delegates appeal for support.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Demand that Lenin's notes on the Georgian Affair be read to the Congress — the party must hear his views.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -5, reputation: 15, survival: 0.55, response: "You insist on transparency. The triumvirate blocks you, arguing that Lenin's notes were written while he was ill and do not represent his considered judgment. Your principled stand is defeated but remembered — by both sides."},
        {text: "Support the triumvirate in burying Lenin's notes — the party cannot be governed from a sickbed.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -10, survival: 0.9, response: "You help suppress Lenin's final political intervention. The rationalization is that Lenin was too ill to form proper judgments. It is a transparent lie, but one the majority accepts. Stalin is grateful for your complicity."},
        {text: "Privately approach Stalin and suggest he offer a token concession to the Georgians to defuse the situation.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You advise Stalin to make a tactical retreat — some cosmetic concession to Georgian autonomy that costs nothing substantive. Stalin appreciates political advice that serves his interests. The Georgians get empty gestures while real power stays centralized."},
        {text: "Focus your Congress speech on economic development in the Caucasus — address the Georgian question through investment rather than politics.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You reframe the Georgian question as an economic development issue. Build railways, fund industries, improve living standards — and national grievances will fade. This materialist argument sidesteps the explosive political dimensions."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The party apparatus under Stalin is increasingly controlling who can speak at the Congress and what they can say. Delegate selection is being managed to ensure loyal majorities. Some old revolutionaries who once debated freely now find themselves excluded from committees or denied speaking time. The bureaucratization of the party is becoming its defining feature.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Accept the new reality and work within the system — adapt to the apparatus or be crushed by it.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: -5, survival: 0.95, response: "You internalize the new rules. Submit speeches for pre-approval. Lobby for committee assignments through the Secretariat. Network with Stalin's appointees. The age of free revolutionary debate is over; the age of bureaucratic politics has begun."},
        {text: "Protest the managed delegate selection — party congresses should represent the membership, not the apparatus.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -10, reputation: 15, survival: 0.55, response: "You challenge the rigged procedures. Your protest is heard, noted, and overruled. The apparatus has learned that controlling delegate selection is more effective than winning arguments. You have identified the mechanism of your own marginalization."},
        {text: "Cultivate a relationship with Molotov, Stalin's key organizational deputy, to ensure you remain in the loop.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You build ties with Molotov, who handles much of the Secretariat's day-to-day work. Access to Molotov means access to the apparatus. Your pragmatic networking ensures you are not excluded from the emerging power structure."},
        {text: "Build your own network of supporters in the provinces through personal visits and favors.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You travel to provincial party organizations, building relationships and doing favors. A personal network provides some independence from the central apparatus. But Stalin's Secretariat controls transfers — your people can be moved at will."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Comintern is grappling with the failure of revolution in Germany. The German Communist Party attempted an uprising in October 1923 and failed disastrously. Blame must be assigned. Zinoviev, as Comintern chairman, is vulnerable. Trotsky's supporters argue that Zinoviev's poor leadership doomed the German revolution. Zinoviev blames the German party's local leadership.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Blame the German Communist leadership — they lacked revolutionary courage at the decisive moment.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You pin blame on the German comrades, protecting the Soviet leadership. This is the politically safest position — foreign communists cannot retaliate in Soviet factional politics. Zinoviev is relieved that you are not pointing the finger at him."},
        {text: "Argue that Zinoviev's Comintern provided inadequate guidance and support to the German uprising.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.75, response: "You criticize Zinoviev's management of the German situation. This subtly aids Stalin and Trotsky, both of whom are happy to see Zinoviev weakened. But Zinoviev is still powerful and vindictive."},
        {text: "Draw the lesson that world revolution is not imminent — we must focus on building socialism in the USSR.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You use the German failure to argue for turning inward. This foreshadows Stalin's 'Socialism in One Country' doctrine, which will be formally articulated next year. Your conclusion from the German debacle aligns with the emerging consensus."},
        {text: "Propose reforming Comintern strategy to focus on long-term party building rather than revolutionary adventures.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You advocate a strategic shift from revolutionary putschism to patient organizational work. Build strong communist parties through trade union work, education, and electoral participation. This pragmatic approach eventually becomes Comintern policy."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The debate over economic policy intensifies. Preobrazhensky, aligned with Trotsky, publishes 'The New Economics,' arguing that the peasantry must fund industrialization through unequal exchange — the state should buy agricultural products cheaply and sell industrial goods dearly. Bukharin counters that the peasant alliance must be preserved. The theoretical debate has enormous practical implications.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support Bukharin's defense of the peasant alliance — the NEP depends on keeping the peasantry content.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You back Bukharin's pro-peasant economics. His famous appeal to the peasants to 'enrich yourselves' captures the spirit of the NEP. The Stalin-Bukharin alliance holds firm. But Bukharin's position will be denounced as a 'Right deviation' within five years."},
        {text: "Back Preobrazhensky's analysis — rapid industrialization requires extracting surplus from agriculture.", loyalty: -10, cunning: 0, reputation: 5, survival: 0.6, response: "You support the economic logic of 'primitive socialist accumulation.' It is analytically powerful but politically toxic — it means squeezing the peasantry. Stalin will eventually implement exactly this program through forced collectivization, while executing its theoretical advocates."},
        {text: "Argue for a balanced approach — gradual industrialization funded by voluntary peasant savings and foreign trade.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You propose a middle way that avoids both extremes. Moderate industrial growth funded through multiple sources. This balanced approach lacks the drama of the factional positions but represents sound economics."},
        {text: "Focus on attracting foreign investment and technology — let Western capital help industrialize the Soviet Union.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You advocate for foreign concessions and technology transfers. Lenin had already granted some foreign concessions. Importing Western industrial expertise could accelerate development without squeezing the peasantry. But reliance on capitalist investment makes ideologues nervous."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "A struggle over the party's cultural policy emerges. Proletarian culture advocates (Proletkult) demand that only art created by workers can serve the revolution. Others argue that the party should utilize the best of bourgeois culture while developing new socialist forms. Trotsky's 'Literature and Revolution' argues for creative freedom during the transition period. The debate reflects deeper questions about what kind of society socialism is building.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support Proletkult — only genuinely proletarian art can serve socialist construction.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 0, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You back the proletarian culture movement. Its artists produce politically committed if sometimes crude work. The movement will be gradually brought under party control — autonomous cultural organizations are not tolerated indefinitely."},
        {text: "Back Trotsky's call for creative freedom — art cannot be directed by committee.", loyalty: -5, cunning: -5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.75, response: "You defend artistic freedom. Trotsky's position allows for a flowering of experimental art — constructivism, futurism, avant-garde cinema. But supporting any position identified with Trotsky carries increasing political risk."},
        {text: "Argue that the party should control cultural policy directly — art is too important to leave to artists.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You advocate direct party oversight of cultural production. This is the position that will ultimately triumph under Stalin's doctrine of Socialist Realism. Anticipating the direction of cultural policy demonstrates political foresight."},
        {text: "Propose using culture as a practical tool — literacy campaigns, educational films, propaganda posters — rather than debating abstract aesthetics.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You redirect the cultural debate toward practical goals. Millions of Soviet citizens are still illiterate. Focus on basic education, not theoretical arguments about proletarian aesthetics. Your pragmatism cuts through the intellectual posturing."}
      ]
    }
  ],
  13: [
    {
      text: "Lenin is dead, and his body is being embalmed against his known wishes for a simple burial. A grandiose mausoleum is planned for Red Square. Krupskaya protests — Lenin would have hated this. But Stalin is constructing a cult of Lenin as a quasi-religious phenomenon, with Lenin's writings treated as sacred texts and his preserved body as a secular relic. You must navigate the politics of mourning.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Enthusiastically support the mausoleum and the cult of Lenin — the masses need symbols to believe in.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You help build the Lenin cult. The mausoleum, the Lenin Corners in every workplace, the catechism-like study of his works — all serve to legitimize the current leadership as Lenin's true heirs. Stalin controls who interprets Lenin, which means Stalin controls the cult."},
        {text: "Quietly support Krupskaya's wish for a simple burial — respect Lenin's own stated preferences.", loyalty: -5, cunning: -5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.7, response: "You side with Krupskaya. It is a moral stance that honors Lenin's memory. But the cult of Lenin has powerful political utility, and those who oppose it appear to be opposing Lenin's legacy itself — a masterful manipulation by Stalin."},
        {text: "Focus on publishing and interpreting Lenin's theoretical works — control the narrative of what Lenin actually believed.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You become involved in the Lenin Institute, which collects and publishes his writings. This is enormously important — controlling which texts are emphasized and how they are interpreted shapes every political debate. Whoever controls Lenin's legacy controls the party."},
        {text: "Deliver a eulogy at a memorial meeting that subtly positions your own political views as Lenin's true inheritance.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You give a carefully crafted speech connecting Lenin's ideas to your own positions. Everyone is doing this — Stalin, Trotsky, Bukharin, Zinoviev all claim to be Lenin's truest disciples. The dead Lenin speaks through whoever has the loudest megaphone."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The 'Literary Discussion' erupts when Trotsky publishes 'Lessons of October,' drawing parallels between Zinoviev and Kamenev's opposition to the October Revolution in 1917 and their current political hesitations. The triumvirate retaliates by inventing 'Trotskyism' as an anti-Leninist deviation, dredging up every disagreement Trotsky ever had with Lenin. Every party cell must pass resolutions. You serve on your district committee.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Lead the denunciation of Trotskyism in your district — organize meetings, draft resolutions, collect signatures.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You become a local enforcer of the anti-Trotsky campaign. Resolutions condemning Trotskyism pour from your district. The apparatus rewards this kind of organizational enthusiasm. You have proven you can mobilize the membership on command."},
        {text: "Fulfill the minimum requirements — pass the required resolution without personal attacks on Trotsky.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You do what is required and nothing more. The resolution passes. You avoid adding personal venom to the campaign. This minimal compliance keeps you safe without making you conspicuous as either a zealot or a dissenter."},
        {text: "Speak up for Trotsky's historical contributions while condemning his current 'errors' — a balanced approach.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.75, response: "You try to be fair to Trotsky's record while criticizing his current positions. The apparatus views this as insufficient — the campaign demands total condemnation, not balanced assessment. Your moderation is recorded as suspicious softness."},
        {text: "Use the campaign to build relationships with rising apparatus figures who are leading the anti-Trotsky charge.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You network with the ambitious young apparatchiks running the anti-Trotsky campaign in their districts. These are the coming men of the party — Kaganovich, Kirov, Zhdanov. Building ties with them now creates a network that will sustain your career for years."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Stalin articulates 'Socialism in One Country' — the theory that the Soviet Union can build a socialist society without waiting for world revolution. Trotsky's 'Permanent Revolution' insists that socialism in an isolated, backward country is impossible without international revolutionary support. The theoretical debate has become a proxy for the succession struggle.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Embrace Socialism in One Country — it gives the party a practical mission and the Russian people hope.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.95, response: "You become an advocate for Stalin's doctrine. It is emotionally compelling — after years of waiting for world revolution that never comes, building socialism at home offers concrete purpose. The doctrine appeals to Russian patriotism and party pride."},
        {text: "Defend Permanent Revolution — Marxist theory clearly shows socialism cannot survive in one country alone.", loyalty: -15, cunning: -10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.5, response: "You defend Trotsky's theoretical position. It has strong roots in Marxist internationalism. But the party is tired of waiting for foreign revolutions that keep failing. Your theoretical correctness costs you politically."},
        {text: "Argue that the two positions are not as different as they appear — we build socialism here while supporting revolution abroad.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You attempt a synthesis. In practice, the Soviet Union does both — building domestically while supporting foreign communists through the Comintern. Your attempt to bridge the gap shows intellectual agility, though both factions may view it as fence-sitting."},
        {text: "Avoid the theoretical debate entirely — focus your Congress contributions on practical economic questions.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You refuse to engage in what you privately consider a theological dispute dressed up as political theory. Practical economic management is your contribution. But in a party that takes theory seriously, ignoring the debate means forfeiting influence over the party's direction."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Trotsky is increasingly isolated. He has been removed as War Commissar and reassigned to minor economic posts. His supporters in the military and universities are being transferred to remote positions. His health is poor — he suffers from mysterious recurring fevers. Some suspect he is being slowly poisoned. A former ally of Trotsky approaches you asking for help finding a new position after being demoted.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Help the former Trotskyist find a position — maintaining relationships across factional lines is wise.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You quietly assist the demoted official. It is a small act of kindness and political insurance — if the political winds shift, having friends in the opposition camp could prove valuable. But the apparatus monitors who helps Trotskyists."},
        {text: "Refuse to help and report the approach to the party authorities — associating with Trotskyists is dangerous.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -10, survival: 0.85, response: "You turn the man away and file a report. The apparatus rewards vigilance against opposition contacts. Your former acquaintance is transferred even further from Moscow. You have demonstrated that loyalty to the apparatus overrides personal bonds."},
        {text: "Help discreetly but extract a promise of future loyalty — this person owes you now.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You provide quiet assistance while building a network of obligation. The person you help today may be in a position to help you tomorrow — or may be forced to testify against you. In Soviet politics, favors create both allies and vulnerabilities."},
        {text: "Advise the person to write a public recantation of Trotskyism — that is the only way back into good standing.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You offer practical advice: publicly renounce Trotsky and his ideas, submit a statement to the party press, and request a review of your case. Self-criticism and recantation are the approved path back from political disgrace."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Lenin's Testament is read aloud at a closed session of the Central Committee before the Congress. The room is tense as Lenin's criticisms of Stalin, Trotsky, Zinoviev, Kamenev, Bukharin, and Pyatakov are heard. The postscript calling for Stalin's removal as General Secretary creates a moment of genuine crisis. Kamenev proposes that the Testament not be published and that Stalin remain in his post. A vote is called.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Vote to suppress the Testament and keep Stalin as General Secretary — the triumvirate's unity must hold.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You vote with the majority to bury Lenin's last wish. Stalin offers his resignation — a theatrical gesture he knows will be refused. The Testament is locked away. You have participated in one of the most consequential cover-ups in Soviet history."},
        {text: "Vote to publish the Testament and remove Stalin — Lenin's dying wish must be honored.", loyalty: -15, cunning: -10, reputation: 15, survival: 0.45, response: "You vote to fulfill Lenin's explicit request. You are in the minority. Trotsky himself does not press the issue with sufficient force. Your vote is recorded, and Stalin will remember those who tried to end his career. Few of them will survive the decade."},
        {text: "Propose a compromise — publish the Testament but do not act on it immediately; let the Congress decide.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.7, response: "You suggest a middle path: transparency without immediate consequences. The triumvirate rejects this — publishing the Testament would be devastating regardless of what action follows. Your compromise fails but shows you tried to find a way forward."},
        {text: "Abstain from the vote — you cannot bring yourself to suppress Lenin's wishes or to oppose the current leadership.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 0, survival: 0.75, response: "You sit out this historic vote. Your abstention pleases no one but damages you less than either a yes or no. In the memoirs and histories that will be written, your absence from this moment will be a small mercy."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Congress must elect a new Central Committee. Stalin's apparatus controls the nominating process. The composition of the Central Committee will determine which faction controls the party. Trotsky's supporters are being systematically excluded from the nomination list. Some protest; most submit quietly. Your own name is on the proposed list — for now.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Express gratitude for your nomination and vote for the entire slate without objection.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.95, response: "You accept the managed election process and support the apparatus slate. Your compliance ensures your continued membership on the Central Committee. In a system where the nominating process determines the outcome, accepting the process is accepting the power behind it."},
        {text: "Propose adding some Trotsky supporters to the slate in the interest of party unity.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.6, response: "You advocate for a more representative Central Committee. The apparatus rebuffs your suggestion — the whole point of controlling nominations is to exclude opponents. Your advocacy for inclusion marks you as sympathetic to the opposition."},
        {text: "Lobby behind the scenes to ensure your allies are included on the nomination list alongside you.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You work the corridors, trading favors and making deals to get your people on the slate. This is how Soviet politics actually works — not through public speeches but through private negotiations with the apparatus operators."},
        {text: "Propose that Central Committee members should be elected by secret ballot rather than open show of hands.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 0, reputation: 10, survival: 0.7, response: "You call for secret balloting. The proposal is rejected — open voting allows the apparatus to monitor who supports whom. Your democratic impulse is noted as a potential deviation. Secret ballots would undermine the entire system of managed elections."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The party is expanding rapidly, and new members need ideological education. A network of party schools and study circles is being established. The question is what to teach. Stalin's supporters want to emphasize 'Leninism' — as they define it. Trotsky's followers want a broader curriculum including Marx, Engels, and yes, Trotsky's own works. The battle for the party's intellectual soul is fought in classrooms.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support a curriculum centered on 'Foundations of Leninism' — Stalin's recent lectures define the orthodoxy.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You promote Stalin's version of Leninism as the core curriculum. His lectures, published as a book, become the standard text for party education. By defining what Leninism means, Stalin controls the ideological framework within which all debates occur."},
        {text: "Advocate for a comprehensive curriculum covering Marx, Engels, Lenin, and contemporary debates — including Trotsky.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 0, reputation: 10, survival: 0.7, response: "You argue for intellectual breadth. Including Trotsky's works in the curriculum is increasingly controversial — his ideas are being labeled as deviations. Your open-mindedness marks you as potentially disloyal to the emerging orthodox line."},
        {text: "Focus party education on practical skills — economics, administration, agronomy — rather than theoretical disputes.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You propose practical education for practical cadres. The party needs people who can run factories and farms, not just recite Marx. Your pragmatic curriculum produces competent administrators who serve whatever faction holds power."},
        {text: "Volunteer to teach party education courses yourself — shaping young cadres' worldview is an investment in the future.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You become a party educator, directly influencing the next generation. The students you train will remember you. In a system that increasingly rewards personal networks, having a cohort of proteges is invaluable political capital."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "A crisis in economic policy reveals tensions between the state sector and private NEP economy. State-owned trusts are poorly managed and inefficient, unable to compete with nimble private traders. Dzerzhinsky, now heading the Supreme Economic Council, drives himself to exhaustion trying to reform state industry. Meanwhile, 'NEPmen' — private entrepreneurs — visibly prosper, breeding resentment among party faithful.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Defend the NEPmen's role — they provide goods and services the state sector cannot yet deliver.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You argue the case for private enterprise within the NEP framework. The NEPmen are unpopular but economically useful. Bukharin's wing appreciates your support for the market economy. But defending private traders is never comfortable for a communist."},
        {text: "Call for restricting NEPmen through higher taxes and tighter regulations — squeeze them gradually.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You propose a middle course: maintain the NEP framework but increase pressure on private capital. Higher taxes, stricter licensing, preference for state enterprises in procurement. This gradual approach satisfies those who dislike NEPmen without dismantling the NEP."},
        {text: "Demand the abolition of the NEP and return to direct state control of the economy.", loyalty: 0, cunning: -5, reputation: 0, survival: 0.7, response: "You call for ending the NEP prematurely. The leadership is not ready for this step — the NEP still provides economic stability. Your maximalism marks you as an ultra-leftist. Stalin will eventually end the NEP, but on his own timetable and terms."},
        {text: "Focus on improving state enterprise management — the answer is not less private trade but better public enterprise.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.9, response: "You argue for reforming the state sector rather than attacking the private sector. Better management, modern accounting, technical expertise — make state enterprises competitive. Dzerzhinsky, working himself to death on this very problem, appreciates your support."}
      ]
    }
  ],
  14: [
    {
      text: "The triumvirate has shattered. Zinoviev and Kamenev, horrified by Stalin's growing power, have broken with him and formed the 'New Opposition.' At the Congress, the Leningrad delegation — loyal to Zinoviev as party boss of that city — challenges the Moscow-dominated majority. Krupskaya sides with the New Opposition. The atmosphere is electric as the two largest party organizations face off.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Stand firmly with the Stalin-Bukharin majority — they control the apparatus and will certainly win.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.95, response: "You join the overwhelming majority. The Leningrad delegation is drowned out by organized heckling and procedural maneuvers. Zinoviev and Kamenev are humiliated. Stalin sends Kirov to take control of the Leningrad party organization, purging Zinoviev's supporters."},
        {text: "Support the New Opposition — Zinoviev and Kamenev are right that Stalin's bureaucratic machine threatens the party.", loyalty: -15, cunning: -10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.4, response: "You side with the doomed minority. The New Opposition is outvoted at every turn — Stalin's control of delegate selection ensures lopsided majorities. Your courage is real, but in Soviet politics, losing sides do not just lose arguments — they lose careers and eventually lives."},
        {text: "Propose that both sides submit to a party referendum — let the membership decide.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 0, reputation: 10, survival: 0.7, response: "You call for democratic resolution. The very idea terrifies the apparatus — a genuine vote among the membership might produce unpredictable results. Your proposal is dismissed as 'anarcho-syndicalist' thinking. Party democracy is invoked but never practiced."},
        {text: "Focus your speech on the industrialization debate rather than the factional fight — you support moderate industrial growth.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You steer your contribution toward economics. The real substance behind the factional fight is the pace of industrialization — Zinoviev wants faster growth, Bukharin wants to protect the peasant economy. Your moderate position keeps you in the majority without requiring factional commitment."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Bukharin has emerged as Stalin's chief ideological partner, defending the NEP and the alliance with the peasantry. His slogan 'Enrich yourselves!' directed at peasants shocks many communists. He argues that the kulaks — prosperous peasants — will 'grow into socialism' through cooperatives. Zinoviev and Kamenev attack this as a betrayal of Marxism. Where do you stand on the kulak question?",
      choices: [
        {text: "Back Bukharin — the kulaks produce grain, and a well-fed country is a stable country.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You defend the pro-peasant line. It is economically sensible — agricultural surplus funds industrial investment. But Bukharin's 'Enrich yourselves' is politically tone-deaf for a Marxist party. Within four years, the kulaks will be targeted for liquidation as a class."},
        {text: "Agree with the New Opposition that tolerating kulaks means tolerating the growth of rural capitalism.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.6, response: "You take the leftist position on the peasant question. Kulaks represent a class enemy within the countryside. But the Stalin-Bukharin alliance holds firm, and opposing their peasant policy means opposing the dominant coalition."},
        {text: "Propose differentiating between types of peasants — support middle peasants while restricting the wealthiest kulaks.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You craft a nuanced class analysis of the countryside. Not all prosperous peasants are class enemies — distinguish between those who employ hired labor and those who simply farm well. This sophisticated position avoids the extremes of either faction."},
        {text: "Argue that the kulak question will resolve itself as cooperatives and state farms expand — no need for confrontation.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You take the optimistic view that economic evolution will gradually socialize the countryside without coercion. History will prove this wrong — Stalin will choose violent collectivization instead. But in 1925, your evolutionary optimism matches the leadership's public position."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Congress sends Kirov to take over the Leningrad party organization from Zinoviev. Kirov must purge Zinoviev's loyalists and install Stalin's people. It is a delicate operation — Leningrad's workers are genuinely loyal to Zinoviev, who has led the city for years. You are offered a role in the takeover team. The work involves removing people from their positions and replacing them with outsiders.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Accept the assignment enthusiastically — reorganizing Leningrad is important party work.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You participate in the Leningrad purge. Zinoviev's people are systematically removed from every important position. The work is politically profitable — you build connections with Kirov and demonstrate your value to the apparatus. But those you purge remember your role."},
        {text: "Decline politely — you have important work in your current posting that cannot be interrupted.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You avoid the purge assignment. The work of removing established officials is thankless and creates enemies. By staying in your current position, you avoid being identified as an enforcer while maintaining your standing through competent routine work."},
        {text: "Accept but try to be fair — evaluate each Leningrad official individually rather than conducting a wholesale purge.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You bring a measure of fairness to the reorganization. Some Zinoviev-era officials who demonstrate competence and willingness to cooperate are retained. Kirov appreciates your measured approach, though the apparatus wants more thoroughness."},
        {text: "Use the assignment to build your own network in Leningrad — place people who are loyal to you, not just to Stalin.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You exploit the purge to install your own clients alongside Stalin's appointees. Building an independent base in Russia's second city is ambitious and risky — Stalin expects total loyalty from those he empowers, not independent empire-building."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The debate over industrialization intensifies. The New Opposition argues for faster industrial growth funded by higher taxes on peasants and NEPmen. The Stalin-Bukharin alliance insists on a moderate pace that preserves the peasant alliance. Trotsky, though not formally allied with the New Opposition, shares their economic analysis. The party's economic future hangs on this debate.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support gradual industrialization within the NEP framework — Bukharin's economics are sound.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You back moderate industrial growth. This is the official line in 1925. But within three years, Stalin will abandon Bukharin and adopt the opposition's position of rapid industrialization. Those too closely identified with the moderate line will find themselves suddenly on the 'Right.'"},
        {text: "Argue for ambitious but planned industrialization targets based on careful economic analysis.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 10, survival: 0.9, response: "You advocate for industrialization driven by data rather than ideology. Commission proper economic studies, set realistic targets, invest in infrastructure. This technocratic approach transcends factional lines and positions you as a competent administrator regardless of who wins the political battle."},
        {text: "Support the New Opposition's call for rapid industrialization — the country's backwardness is its greatest vulnerability.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.6, response: "You join the call for faster industrial growth. The analysis is correct — the Soviet Union's industrial weakness is dangerous in a hostile world. But supporting the opposition's economic program means supporting the opposition, with all the political consequences that entails."},
        {text: "Propose focusing on light industry and consumer goods rather than heavy industry — give the people a reason to support socialism.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.75, response: "You argue for consumer-oriented development. Workers and peasants are tired of sacrifice — give them goods to buy. This position has limited support, as both factions prioritize heavy industry. The Soviet Union will always choose tanks over toasters."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Stalin introduces changes to the party rules that further strengthen the Secretariat's control over membership and appointments. The 'uchraspred' — the Secretariat's assignments department — now effectively decides every important party posting in the country. Your own next appointment depends on this department's goodwill. A colleague warns you that the uchraspred is compiling dossiers on every party member's political history.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Ensure your own dossier is clean — review your past statements and associations for anything that could be used against you.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You carefully audit your own political history. Have you ever expressed sympathy for any opposition? Have any of your associates fallen from favor? In the new party culture, everyone has a file, and awareness of what is in yours is essential survival knowledge."},
        {text: "Cultivate a relationship with key uchraspred officials — they are the gatekeepers of every career in the party.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: -5, survival: 0.95, response: "You befriend the personnel managers. These mid-level bureaucrats wield enormous informal power. A favorable recommendation from the uchraspred can make your career; an unfavorable one can break it. Investing in relationships with them is pure political pragmatism."},
        {text: "Protest the uchraspred's growing power — appointment decisions should involve more input from local party organizations.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.6, response: "You object to the centralization of appointments. This is a direct challenge to Stalin's power base. The uchraspred system is his primary tool of control. Those who threaten it threaten him personally."},
        {text: "Volunteer for the uchraspred — if you cannot beat the system, join it and gain influence from within.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 15, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You seek to join the personnel apparatus itself. Working inside the uchraspred gives you both information and influence over appointments. The mundane work of reviewing cadre files is the hidden engine of Soviet power."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "At the margins of the Congress, the question of Soviet foreign policy arises. The Locarno Treaties have stabilized Western Europe, reducing the prospects for revolution in Germany. Britain has recognized the Soviet Union but relations remain tense. The Comintern's strategy of supporting colonial liberation movements in Asia offers new revolutionary possibilities. China is in turmoil, with the KMT-CCP alliance under strain.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Prioritize the Chinese revolution — support the alliance between Chiang Kai-shek's KMT and the Chinese Communist Party.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You back the Comintern's current China policy of alliance with the KMT. Stalin personally supports this strategy. When Chiang turns on the Communists in 1927, massacring thousands, this policy will be discredited — but for now it is the official line."},
        {text: "Warn that Chiang Kai-shek is unreliable — the Chinese Communists should maintain independent military forces.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You express skepticism about the KMT alliance. Trotsky shares this view, which makes it politically dangerous despite being strategically sound. The Shanghai massacre of 1927 will prove you right, but being right about a policy Stalin personally championed is not rewarded."},
        {text: "Focus on state-to-state diplomacy rather than revolution — the Soviet Union needs trade agreements and diplomatic recognition more than revolutionary upheaval.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You advocate realist foreign policy. Trade agreements with Britain and Germany benefit the Soviet economy directly. Revolutionary adventures in China are risky and expensive. Your pragmatism aligns with the Narkomindel (foreign ministry) approach."},
        {text: "Argue for building the Red Army's strength as the primary foreign policy tool — military power speaks louder than either diplomacy or revolution.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You advocate military modernization as the foundation of foreign policy. Neither diplomacy nor revolution can protect the Soviet Union without a strong Red Army. Your focus on military preparedness wins support from defense professionals."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Living standards in the cities are improving under the NEP, but inequality is growing. Party members see NEPmen driving cars and dining in restaurants while workers struggle with housing shortages and low wages. Resentment toward the 'new bourgeoisie' is widespread. The party's working-class base demands to know why communists tolerate capitalist profiteers.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Address inequality by improving workers' housing and social services — show the working class that the party delivers.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.9, response: "You champion worker welfare programs. New housing construction, improved canteens, workers' clubs, and kindergartens demonstrate that the party cares. Spending on social infrastructure keeps the working class loyal while avoiding the divisive question of ending the NEP."},
        {text: "Propose higher taxes on NEPmen to fund workers' benefits — redistribution within the system.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You advocate tax-based redistribution. Tax the wealthy NEPmen and invest the proceeds in workers' housing and services. This addresses inequality within the NEP framework without dismantling it. A popular and politically safe position."},
        {text: "Argue that inequality is a temporary but necessary evil — the NEP will eventually raise everyone's standard of living.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.8, response: "You try to explain that market economies produce inequality but also growth. Workers are better off than during War Communism, even if NEPmen are better off still. This honest economic reasoning is ideologically uncomfortable for a communist party."},
        {text: "Stoke class resentment against NEPmen — they represent the enemy class and should be suppressed.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You channel working-class anger against private traders. This populist approach wins applause from the party base. But if taken too far, it undermines the NEP that the leadership supports. Stalin will use exactly this kind of class warfare rhetoric when he turns against the NEP in 1928."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Frunze, the new War Commissar who replaced Trotsky, dies during surgery under suspicious circumstances. Rumors circulate that the operation was unnecessary and that Stalin wanted Frunze removed. Voroshilov, a loyal Stalin ally with limited military competence, replaces him. The military leadership is being reshaped for political reliability rather than professional ability.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Accept Voroshilov's appointment without question — the party's right to appoint military leaders is absolute.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You endorse the new War Commissar. Voroshilov is personally brave but strategically limited. His appointment signals that political loyalty matters more than military competence in Stalin's system. This principle will have devastating consequences in 1941."},
        {text: "Quietly express concern to trusted colleagues about Frunze's death — the circumstances are disturbing.", loyalty: -5, cunning: -5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.7, response: "You share your unease about Frunze's suspicious death. The writer Pilnyak will publish a thinly veiled fictional account of the affair. But questioning the circumstances of a leader's death is implicitly questioning the leadership itself."},
        {text: "Focus on strengthening the Red Army's technical capabilities regardless of who leads it — modernization transcends politics.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You concentrate on military modernization — tanks, aircraft, communications — rather than leadership politics. Technical competence is always valued, and your expertise becomes a resource that any military leader needs, regardless of their political connections."},
        {text: "Cultivate a relationship with Voroshilov — as the new War Commissar, he will have enormous patronage to distribute.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 15, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You ingratiate yourself with the new military chief. Voroshilov's personal network will dominate the military for over a decade. Having his confidence opens doors to military-industrial resources and appointments. An investment in political patronage."}
      ]
    }
  ],
  15: [
    {
      text: "The United Opposition — a desperate alliance of Trotsky, Zinoviev, and Kamenev — stages a demonstration on the tenth anniversary of the October Revolution in November 1927. Their supporters unfurl banners reading 'Carry Out Lenin's Testament' and 'Against Opportunism, Against the Split.' The GPU disperses the demonstrators. The Congress must decide the fate of the oppositionists.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Demand the immediate expulsion and arrest of all opposition leaders — they have violated the faction ban and staged an anti-party demonstration.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You call for the harshest measures. Trotsky and Zinoviev are indeed expelled from the party. Trotsky will be exiled to Alma-Ata and then deported from the USSR entirely. Your hardline stance earns the apparatus's approval."},
        {text: "Vote for expulsion but argue against criminal prosecution — political opponents should not be treated as criminals.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You draw a line between party discipline and state repression. Expelling oppositionists from the party is one thing; prosecuting them as criminals is another. This moderate position will be overtaken by events — within a decade, opposition will indeed be criminalized."},
        {text: "Propose allowing the opposition leaders to recant and be readmitted — destruction of old revolutionaries serves no one.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.75, response: "You advocate mercy through self-criticism. Zinoviev and Kamenev will indeed recant and be readmitted temporarily, only to be expelled again and eventually executed. Your proposal is adopted but proves meaningless in the long run."},
        {text: "Use the anti-opposition campaign to demonstrate your own loyalty — organize denunciation meetings in your district.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You become a local organizer of the anti-opposition campaign. Your district produces model resolutions condemning the United Opposition. The apparatus appreciates efficient political mobilization. You have proven you can deliver when the leadership demands collective action."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The War Scare of 1927 grips the Soviet Union. Britain has broken diplomatic relations. Chinese Nationalists have massacred Communists in Shanghai. Poland and Romania are seen as potential invasion routes. Stalin uses the external threat to rally support and silence domestic opposition — questioning the leadership during a war scare is tantamount to treason. Military spending increases dramatically.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Sound the alarm loudly — capitalist encirclement threatens the Soviet Union and we must prepare for war.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You amplify the war scare. Whether the threat is real or manufactured, the political effect is the same — the party rallies around the leadership and opposition becomes treasonous. Your alarmism serves Stalin's domestic political needs perfectly."},
        {text: "Argue that the war scare is exaggerated by the leadership to suppress domestic opposition.", loyalty: -15, cunning: -5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.5, response: "You suggest the war scare is politically manufactured. This is partially true — while external tensions are real, Stalin has magnified them for domestic purposes. But accusing the leadership of fabricating a national security threat is treated as itself a threat to national security."},
        {text: "Focus on concrete military preparedness measures — stockpiling, industrial mobilization planning, border defense.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You turn the war scare into productive preparation. Whether the threat is real or exaggerated, military readiness is never wasted. Your practical approach to defense planning earns respect from both the military and the party leadership."},
        {text: "Propose strengthening diplomatic ties with Germany and other potential allies to counter British hostility.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You advocate diplomatic solutions alongside military preparation. The Rapallo relationship with Germany remains the cornerstone of Soviet foreign policy. Your balanced approach — prepare for war while working for peace — is the sensible middle ground."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The failure of the Chinese revolution weighs heavily on the Congress. Stalin's policy of alliance with Chiang Kai-shek ended in the Shanghai massacre of April 1927, where Nationalist forces slaughtered thousands of Chinese Communists. The opposition had warned this would happen. Stalin must deflect blame. The question of who is responsible for the China debacle becomes a factional weapon.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Blame the Chinese Communist Party leadership for failing to execute Stalin's strategy correctly.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You pin responsibility on the Chinese comrades rather than the Soviet leadership that designed the strategy. Blaming foreign parties for failures of Soviet-directed policy is a well-established practice. The Chinese Communists cannot defend themselves in Soviet factional politics."},
        {text: "Acknowledge the failure but argue it proves the need for better Comintern strategy, not that the approach was fundamentally wrong.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You concede failure while protecting the leadership. The strategy was sound in principle but poorly executed. Better intelligence, clearer communication, more flexible tactics would have produced a different outcome. This face-saving analysis is appreciated."},
        {text: "Argue that the China failure proves the opposition was right — the alliance with bourgeois nationalists was always doomed.", loyalty: -15, cunning: -10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.45, response: "You validate the opposition's analysis. Trotsky had warned repeatedly that Chiang would turn on the Communists. But vindicating the opposition on Stalin's signature foreign policy is political suicide. Being right is the most dangerous thing in Soviet politics."},
        {text: "Propose that the lesson of China is to focus on building strong, independent Communist parties rather than alliances with bourgeois movements.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You draw constructive lessons from the debacle. Independent Communist parties with their own military forces — what Mao will eventually build — are the answer. Your forward-looking analysis avoids the blame game while contributing to genuine strategic thinking."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The NEP is under growing pressure. Grain collections are falling as peasants withhold produce — the state's industrial goods are too expensive and scarce to motivate selling grain at official prices. Stalin has personally traveled to Siberia to oversee forced grain collections, reviving the coercive methods of War Communism. The turn against the NEP is beginning. Bukharin is alarmed.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support Stalin's emergency grain collection measures — feeding the cities is a priority that justifies coercion.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You back the forced grain collections. This marks the beginning of the end for the NEP and the beginning of the end for the Stalin-Bukharin alliance. You have positioned yourself on Stalin's side as he prepares to turn left — ahead of the storm that will engulf Bukharin."},
        {text: "Defend the NEP and oppose forced grain collection — coercion will only make the supply crisis worse.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 0, reputation: 5, survival: 0.7, response: "You defend market mechanisms. Bukharin shares your view. But Stalin has decided that the NEP cannot deliver the grain needed for rapid industrialization. Your economic logic is correct but politically you are siding with the emerging 'Right deviation.'"},
        {text: "Propose a package of measures to make grain sales more attractive — better industrial goods, consumer incentives, improved transport.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You advocate carrots rather than sticks. If peasants had goods to buy, they would sell grain willingly. But the Soviet industrial sector cannot produce enough consumer goods. Your constructive proposal runs into the structural limitations of the economy."},
        {text: "Argue that the grain crisis proves the need for collective farming — individual peasant agriculture cannot feed an industrializing nation.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You make the case for collectivization. This is where Stalin is heading, though the full violence of forced collectivization is not yet apparent. By advocating collective farming now, you position yourself perfectly for the coming policy revolution."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The First Five-Year Plan is being drafted. Ambitious targets for industrial production — steel, coal, electricity, machinery — will transform the Soviet Union from an agrarian into an industrial nation. Two versions exist: an 'optimal' variant with extremely ambitious targets and a 'minimal' variant with more conservative goals. The choice will determine the pace of Soviet industrialization.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support the optimal variant — the Soviet Union must industrialize at maximum speed to survive in a hostile world.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You back the ambitious targets. Stalin adopts the optimal variant and then increases the targets further. The First Five-Year Plan will be declared complete in four years despite massive shortfalls. Your enthusiasm for ambitious planning matches the leadership's mood."},
        {text: "Advocate for the minimal variant — unrealistic targets will lead to waste, bottlenecks, and human suffering.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.7, response: "You argue for achievable targets. This is economically sound — Gosplan's own experts prefer the minimal variant. But political dynamics demand revolutionary ambition, not careful planning. Supporting modest targets is labeled as 'Right opportunism.'"},
        {text: "Propose that targets should be adjusted annually based on actual performance — planning must be flexible.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You advocate adaptive planning. Set ambitious goals but adjust them based on real-world results. This rational approach to planning is undermined in practice by the political impossibility of admitting targets were too high."},
        {text: "Focus on securing the best possible targets for your own sector or region — let others fight about the overall plan.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You play the planning game locally, negotiating for targets that are achievable in your area while appearing ambitious. Set targets you can meet, then report fulfillment. This is how the Soviet planning system actually functions — the appearance of ambition with the reality of negotiated minimums."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Zinoviev and Kamenev have capitulated, submitting humiliating public recantations of their opposition views in exchange for readmission to the party. Trotsky, characteristically, refuses to recant and is exiled to Alma-Ata. The spectacle of once-powerful leaders groveling before the apparatus is both disturbing and instructive. Some opposition supporters must decide whether to follow Zinoviev's path of submission or Trotsky's path of defiance.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Publicly praise Zinoviev and Kamenev's recantation as proof that honest communists can correct their errors.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You celebrate the recantations. The ritual humiliation of former leaders reinforces the lesson that resistance is futile and submission is the only path back. Your approval of the process helps normalize the culture of forced self-criticism."},
        {text: "Express private admiration for Trotsky's refusal to recant — at least he maintained his dignity.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.6, response: "You quietly respect Trotsky's defiance. But private admiration for an enemy of the party is dangerous. The GPU monitors conversations and associations. Expressing sympathy for Trotsky, even privately, risks being reported and labeled a hidden oppositionist."},
        {text: "Use the example of the recantations to encourage any wavering members in your network to submit early — resistance only brings harsher punishment.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You become a practical counselor, advising former opposition sympathizers to submit before it is too late. Early recantation brings milder consequences. This helpful cynicism saves some people from worse fates and builds gratitude in your network."},
        {text: "Propose that the party establish a formal process for rehabilitating former oppositionists — clear rules for re-admission.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You suggest institutionalizing the recantation process. Clear criteria for what constitutes acceptable self-criticism, formal review procedures, defined probationary periods. This bureaucratic approach appeals to those who want the opposition question resolved systematically."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Congress debates collectivization of agriculture. The question is no longer whether to collectivize but how fast and by what methods. Some advocate gradual, voluntary collectivization through persuasion and economic incentives. Others want rapid, state-directed transformation of the countryside. The kulaks — prosperous peasants — are increasingly defined as class enemies who must be eliminated.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support rapid collectivization — the individual peasant farm is an obstacle to socialist construction that must be overcome quickly.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You advocate speed and force. This is the direction Stalin is heading. Within two years, rapid collectivization will devastate the countryside, causing famine and the deportation of millions of kulaks. But in 1927, the full horror is not yet visible, and supporting collectivization is politically correct."},
        {text: "Argue for gradual, voluntary collectivization — force the peasants into collectives and you will destroy agriculture.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.7, response: "You warn against coercion. Bukharin shares this view and will be labeled a Right deviationist for it. Your caution is vindicated by the catastrophic results of forced collectivization, but vindication comes too late to matter politically."},
        {text: "Propose a pilot program — collectivize a few districts as an experiment before committing to nationwide transformation.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You suggest testing before scaling. Some pilot collective farms do exist and show mixed results. But the political dynamic demands revolutionary transformation, not careful experimentation. Your scientific approach is overridden by ideological fervor."},
        {text: "Focus on the technical requirements of collectivization — tractors, trained agronomists, storage facilities — the infrastructure that must precede the social transformation.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.85, response: "You emphasize that collective farms need machinery and expertise to succeed. Without tractors, collective farming is just individual farming on a larger scale. Your technical focus is correct — the lack of agricultural machinery will be a major factor in collectivization's disastrous results."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Stalin is moving against Bukharin, his former ally. Bukharin privately tells Kamenev that Stalin's policies will lead to catastrophe and that 'Stalin will strangle us.' This conversation is leaked and used against Bukharin. The 'Right deviation' — Bukharin, Rykov, Tomskii — is being isolated. Choosing sides in this new factional fight will determine your fate.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Side decisively with Stalin against the Right deviation — the Right is as dangerous as the Left was.", loyalty: 15, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.9, response: "You join the campaign against Bukharin. Having just helped destroy the Left Opposition, the apparatus now turns its machinery on the Right. Your willingness to attack former allies demonstrates the total loyalty Stalin demands."},
        {text: "Defend Bukharin's economic views — the NEP and the peasant alliance remain essential for Soviet development.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.5, response: "You stand by Bukharin. It is an act of intellectual and personal loyalty. But the apparatus that crushed Trotsky, Zinoviev, and Kamenev will crush Bukharin with equal efficiency. Those who stand with him will share his fate."},
        {text: "Remain silent and wait to see which direction the wind blows — this factional shift is too dangerous to engage with prematurely.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You stay quiet during the transition. The alliance that governed the party for three years is breaking apart, and choosing the wrong side could be fatal. Your silence is noted but not punished — in a fast-moving factional fight, silence is a defensible position."},
        {text: "Support Stalin's turn to rapid industrialization and collectivization on its merits — regardless of the factional dimension.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You endorse the policy shift without framing it as anti-Bukharin. Rapid industrialization is necessary; collectivization is the only way to feed the cities. By focusing on policy rather than personalities, you support Stalin while maintaining some dignity."}
      ]
    }
  ],
  16: [
    {
      text: "Forced collectivization is sweeping the countryside with devastating violence. Kulaks — defined broadly to include any peasant who resists — are being deported by the millions to labor camps in Siberia and Central Asia. Families are separated, property confiscated, and villages destroyed. Stalin's article 'Dizziness from Success' blames local officials for 'excesses.' You receive reports from your region describing horrific conditions.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Implement collectivization with maximum vigor — the class enemy in the countryside must be liquidated.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 0, reputation: -10, survival: 0.8, response: "You drive collectivization ruthlessly. Deportation quotas are met. Collective farms are established on schedule. The human cost is staggering — families destroyed, communities shattered, lives lost. But your district reports successful completion of the plan."},
        {text: "Use Stalin's 'Dizziness from Success' article to slow down and correct the worst excesses in your area.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You cite Stalin's own words to moderate the tempo. After the article, peasants temporarily flood out of collectives. Then the pressure resumes. But during the brief pause, you have spared some of the worst violence in your district. A small mercy justified by the leader's own text."},
        {text: "Write a confidential report to the Central Committee documenting the real conditions — famine, resistance, administrative chaos.", loyalty: -5, cunning: -5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.6, response: "You document the catastrophe honestly. The Central Committee receives many such reports and ignores them. Some honest reporters are accused of defeatism or sabotage. Your courage is real but your impact is negligible — the machinery of collectivization grinds on regardless."},
        {text: "Focus on making the collective farms that have been established actually productive — the political battle is over, now comes the economic challenge.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You turn from political enforcement to agricultural management. The new collective farms need seeds, tools, livestock, and trained managers. Your practical focus on making collectivization work is more useful than either championing or opposing it at this point."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The First Five-Year Plan demands impossible industrial targets. Factory managers are caught between plan fulfillment demands and material reality. Shortages of raw materials, skilled labor, and machinery make targets unachievable. When targets are not met, managers are accused of 'wrecking' and sabotage. The Shakhty Trial of engineers in 1928 set the precedent — failure is now treated as a crime.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Report plan fulfillment accurately — honest reporting will allow the leadership to adjust targets.", loyalty: -5, cunning: -10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.55, response: "You submit honest production figures. They show massive shortfalls. The response from above is not gratitude for honesty but suspicion that you are covering for saboteurs. In Stalin's system, admitting failure is itself a form of sabotage."},
        {text: "Inflate your production figures to match the plan — everyone else is doing it.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You join the universal practice of 'report padding.' Your district meets its targets on paper. The real production figures are a fiction, but it is a fiction the system demands. The entire Soviet planning system is built on cascading lies from factory floor to Kremlin."},
        {text: "Demand that engineers and specialists work harder — if targets are not met, someone must be responsible.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -10, survival: 0.8, response: "You scapegoat the technical specialists. Engineers and managers are accused of deliberate sabotage. Show trials and purges of 'wreckers' serve to explain away systemic failures. You have contributed to the culture of blame that makes rational economic management impossible."},
        {text: "Propose adjusting targets based on actual capacity — plans should reflect reality, not ideology.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.65, response: "You argue for realistic planning. This is common sense but political heresy. The Five-Year Plan embodies the party's will — suggesting it cannot be fulfilled implies the party is wrong. You find yourself dangerously close to being labeled a Right deviationist."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Syrtsov-Lominadze group has been discovered. Syrtsov, the head of the Russian Republic government, and Lominadze, a young party leader, have been secretly criticizing Stalin's policies — calling collectivization a disaster and the Five-Year Plan unrealistic. They are expelled from the Central Committee. This is the first case of what will become a pattern: any organized criticism of Stalin, even by senior officials, is treated as conspiracy.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Denounce Syrtsov and Lominadze loudly — they have betrayed the party's trust at the highest level.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You condemn the disgraced officials. Your denunciation is one of many. The message is clear: even the most senior officials are not safe if they criticize the General Secretary. The space for honest discussion within the leadership has shrunk to nearly nothing."},
        {text: "Stay silent on the affair — you have no direct involvement and no reason to draw attention to yourself.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You say nothing about the Syrtsov-Lominadze case. It does not directly concern you, and involving yourself — either for or against the accused — only creates risk. In an atmosphere of conspiracy charges, the safest position is to have no position."},
        {text: "Privately worry that your own conversations might be reported — and begin censoring yourself even in trusted company.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "The Syrtsov case teaches you that no conversation is private. You begin speaking in euphemisms, avoiding any statement that could be construed as criticism. The self-censorship that will define Soviet political culture for decades begins in your own mind."},
        {text: "Use the affair to warn subordinates — be careful what you say and to whom, because informers are everywhere.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You pass the lesson down to your network: trust no one, say nothing critical, assume every conversation is reported. This practical advice saves some of your allies from making dangerous statements. The culture of silence and suspicion deepens."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Dekulakization continues. A three-tier classification system categorizes kulaks: Category 1 (to be shot or imprisoned), Category 2 (to be deported to remote regions), Category 3 (to be expelled from their villages to nearby areas). Local officials face quotas for each category. The definition of 'kulak' is elastic — anyone who resists collectivization or has a slightly better house can be labeled one.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Fulfill the dekulakization quotas assigned to your district — the party demands it.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -15, survival: 0.8, response: "You meet your quotas. Families are loaded onto cattle cars for Siberia. Property is confiscated. Some are shot. You have personally overseen the destruction of thousands of lives. The quotas are met, and the district reports are filed. The human cost is not counted."},
        {text: "Classify as many kulaks as possible in Category 3 rather than Category 1 or 2 — minimize the most extreme punishments.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You exercise what discretion you have to mitigate the worst outcomes. Moving families to the less severe category saves lives, though it still involves dispossession and displacement. Your small mercies are noticed by the grateful and the watchful alike."},
        {text: "Report that your district has fewer kulaks than the quota demands — the classification has been applied too broadly.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.65, response: "You challenge the quotas. In doing so, you risk being accused of protecting class enemies. Some officials who argued against excessive dekulakization were themselves dekulakized. Your moral stand may cost you more than it saves others."},
        {text: "Delegate the dekulakization work to subordinates and focus on establishing the new collective farms.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You keep your hands clean by assigning the dirty work to others while focusing on the constructive task of building collective farms. Your subordinates bear the moral burden. You can later claim you were focused on positive construction rather than repression."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "A massive famine is developing in Ukraine, Kazakhstan, and the North Caucasus. Grain is being exported abroad to fund industrial imports while Soviet citizens starve. Internal party reports describe mass death, but public acknowledgment of the famine is forbidden. Foreign journalists are denied access to famine regions. You have direct knowledge of conditions in an affected area.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Maintain the official fiction that there is no famine — report that grain collections are proceeding normally.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -10, survival: 0.85, response: "You deny the famine in your reports. Millions are dying, but the grain exports continue. Industrial machinery is purchased with the proceeds. You have participated in one of the greatest cover-ups in history. Most officials make the same choice."},
        {text: "Send a private, classified report to the Central Committee describing the real conditions — not for publication, just for internal awareness.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.7, response: "You try to inform the leadership through confidential channels. Stalin and the Politburo are already aware of the famine — they are deliberately using it as a weapon against peasant resistance. Your report tells them nothing they do not know and marks you as someone who might talk."},
        {text: "Quietly divert some grain from export shipments to feed the starving in your area — save who you can.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.6, response: "You skim grain from export consignments and distribute it locally. This unauthorized action saves some lives but puts you at enormous risk. Diverting state resources is classified as theft of socialist property — a capital offense. Your conscience is clear but your position is perilous."},
        {text: "Request a transfer to a different region — you cannot bear to witness what is happening but lack the power to stop it.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.8, response: "You flee the famine zone. The transfer removes you from direct complicity but also from any ability to help. It is the response of someone who cannot stomach what the system demands but cannot bring themselves to resist it either."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Congress celebrates the achievements of the First Five-Year Plan, which has been declared 'fulfilled in four years.' The rhetoric of achievement is deafening. New cities have been built, enormous factories constructed, dams erected. But the human cost — forced labor, famine, deportation — is hidden behind triumphalist statistics. You must deliver a speech to the Congress.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Deliver an enthusiastic celebration of industrial achievements — Magnitogorsk, Dneprostroi, Stalingrad Tractor Factory — a new world is being built.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You give a rousing speech about industrial triumphs. The achievements are real — the Soviet Union has built an industrial base from nothing. That it was built on bones is not mentioned. Your enthusiasm is indistinguishable from everyone else's, which is exactly the point."},
        {text: "Focus your speech on technical challenges remaining — problems to solve, targets still to be met, quality improvements needed.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You give a constructive speech about the work ahead. Acknowledging challenges is permissible if framed as problems to overcome rather than failures to explain. Your technical competence and forward-looking perspective mark you as a useful administrator."},
        {text: "Include a brief mention of the human sacrifices that made these achievements possible — honor the workers who gave their lives.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 0, reputation: 10, survival: 0.7, response: "You try to honor the dead within the framework of celebration. Even this oblique acknowledgment of suffering is risky — the official narrative allows only triumph, not tragedy. Some delegates nod in recognition; others glance nervously at their neighbors."},
        {text: "Propose that the Second Five-Year Plan prioritize consumer goods and living standards — the people deserve to enjoy the fruits of their sacrifice.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.75, response: "You argue that having built heavy industry, the next plan should benefit ordinary citizens. This consumer-oriented position has some support but goes against the priority of military-industrial production. The Soviet economy will always choose guns over butter."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The OGPU (secret police) is expanding its role in economic management. Forced labor camps — the growing Gulag system — provide cheap labor for construction projects in remote areas. Prisoners build canals, railways, and mines. The White Sea-Baltic Canal is being constructed entirely by prison labor under horrific conditions. The economic logic of the Gulag is becoming entrenched in Soviet planning.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support the use of prison labor for economic development — enemies of the people should contribute to socialist construction.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -10, survival: 0.85, response: "You endorse the Gulag economy. The logic is compelling from a planning perspective — free labor for the most difficult projects. That the 'prisoners' are mostly innocent is not a factor in economic calculations. Your support helps legitimize the system."},
        {text: "Propose that prison labor should meet minimum humanitarian standards — even prisoners have basic needs.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 0, reputation: 10, survival: 0.65, response: "You call for reform of camp conditions. This is a dangerous position — it implies the current conditions are unacceptable, which implies criticism of the OGPU. The security apparatus does not appreciate suggestions about how to run its camps."},
        {text: "Focus on competing for resources with the Gulag system — your industrial projects need free labor that the camps are absorbing.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You object to the Gulag on practical grounds — it diverts labor from regular industrial projects. This technocratic objection avoids moral questions while addressing a genuine economic competition between the planned and camp economies."},
        {text: "Stay silent about the Gulag system — acknowledging its existence or expressing any opinion about it is dangerous.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You pretend the Gulag does not exist. It is an open secret — everyone knows about the camps but no one discusses them publicly. Your silence protects you from involvement in a system that devours both prisoners and administrators with equal appetite."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Ryutin, a mid-level party official, has circulated a document calling Stalin 'the evil genius of the Russian Revolution' and demanding his removal. The 'Ryutin Platform' is the most direct attack on Stalin since the opposition was crushed. Stalin demands the death penalty for Ryutin. Kirov and others on the Politburo resist, arguing that executing a party member for expressing political views would set a catastrophic precedent.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support Stalin's demand for the death penalty — Ryutin has committed an act of political terrorism against the party.", loyalty: 15, cunning: 0, reputation: -15, survival: 0.8, response: "You call for Ryutin's execution. Most of the Politburo resists, and Ryutin is imprisoned rather than shot — for now. But you have demonstrated willingness to cross the line into killing party members for political opposition. Stalin remembers who supported him."},
        {text: "Side with Kirov — imprisonment is sufficient, and executing party members for political views would be a terrible precedent.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.75, response: "You join those opposing the death penalty for Ryutin. The precedent matters — once you execute one oppositionist, where does it stop? Kirov's position prevails for now. But the precedent will be broken within a few years, with consequences for millions."},
        {text: "Vote with the majority — whatever the Politburo decides, you support.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You follow the consensus, which settles on imprisonment without execution. This gives you cover regardless of how the situation develops. If the death penalty becomes standard later, you did not oppose it; if it remains exceptional, you did not demand it."},
        {text: "Argue that Ryutin should be expelled and exiled but not imprisoned — make him a non-person rather than a martyr.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You propose a middle ground — remove Ryutin from political life without creating a precedent for killing party members. Your suggestion is not adopted, but it demonstrates your preference for measured punishment over maximum severity."}
      ]
    }
  ],
  17: [
    {
      text: "The 'Congress of Victors' opens in an atmosphere of enforced triumphalism. Former oppositionists — Zinoviev, Kamenev, Bukharin, Rykov, Tomskii — deliver humiliating self-criticisms, praising Stalin and confessing their past 'errors.' The ritual degradation of old revolutionaries is both pitiful and terrifying. You watch from the floor as men who once shaped history grovel before the General Secretary.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Join the applause enthusiastically when former oppositionists deliver their self-criticisms — their humiliation validates the party line.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You clap loudly as proud old Bolsheviks debase themselves. The ritual of self-criticism serves to demonstrate that resistance to Stalin is futile and that submission is the only path. Your enthusiastic participation signals complete alignment with the system."},
        {text: "Sit quietly during the self-criticisms — neither applauding nor showing sympathy.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You watch in silence. The spectacle of forced self-criticism is designed to humiliate its subjects and intimidate its audience. Your stillness could be read as disapproval or as dignified restraint. In the current atmosphere, ambiguity is a survival strategy."},
        {text: "Approach one of the former oppositionists privately to express sympathy and ask if they need anything.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.55, response: "You make a private gesture of humanity. It is noticed — by the NKVD, which monitors all contacts with former oppositionists. Your kindness may be used as evidence of opposition sympathies when the purges reach their full intensity."},
        {text: "Use the occasion to publicly denounce the former oppositionists even more harshly than they denounce themselves.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 5, reputation: -10, survival: 0.8, response: "You pile on, declaring that the oppositionists' self-criticisms are insufficient and insincere. This performative aggression is noted by the apparatus as excessive zeal. In the coming terror, those who denounce most loudly sometimes become suspects themselves — their very enthusiasm seems suspicious."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Whispers circulate through the Congress corridors about an alternative to Stalin. Kirov, the popular Leningrad party chief, is charismatic, relatively moderate, and respected. Some delegates discuss the possibility of moving Kirov to Moscow in a senior role — perhaps even replacing Stalin as General Secretary. The conversations are extremely dangerous, but they reflect genuine discontent among party veterans.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Report the corridor conversations to the NKVD — any discussion of replacing Stalin is counter-revolutionary.", loyalty: 15, cunning: 5, reputation: -15, survival: 0.8, response: "You inform on your fellow delegates. The NKVD files grow thicker. Those whose names you provide will face consequences — perhaps not immediately, but the files will be there when the purges come. You have traded others' futures for your own momentary security."},
        {text: "Listen carefully but say nothing — information about discontent is valuable but dangerous to possess.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You absorb the conversations without participating. Knowing who is discontented is useful intelligence. But knowledge of a conspiracy is itself dangerous — if the plot is discovered, those who knew and did not report are as guilty as those who participated."},
        {text: "Participate cautiously in the discussions — Kirov's leadership might save the party from Stalin's worst tendencies.", loyalty: -15, cunning: -5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.4, response: "You join the whispered conversations about the Kirov alternative. This is the most dangerous thing you can do at this Congress. Many participants in these corridor discussions will not survive the decade. Kirov himself will be assassinated within the year."},
        {text: "Approach Kirov privately and warn him that people are using his name dangerously — he should distance himself from the discussions.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.75, response: "You warn Kirov that his name is being invoked in ways that could endanger him. Whether Kirov knows about or encourages the discussions is unclear. Your warning could be seen as either protective or threatening. Kirov's assassination in December will render all these calculations moot."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The vote for the Central Committee produces a striking result. According to later accounts, Kirov receives nearly unanimous support while Stalin receives significantly fewer votes — perhaps hundreds of negative ballots. The ballots are reportedly destroyed to conceal the embarrassing result. As a member of the counting commission, you witness the tabulation firsthand.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Support the falsification of results — report equal votes for Stalin and Kirov to avoid a crisis.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 15, reputation: -10, survival: 0.85, response: "You participate in altering the count. The official results show near-unanimous support for Stalin. The destroyed ballots represent the last attempt at democratic expression within the party. Your complicity protects you but makes you an accomplice to the death of internal party democracy."},
        {text: "Insist on reporting accurate results — the Congress has the right to know the true vote count.", loyalty: -15, cunning: -15, reputation: 15, survival: 0.35, response: "You demand honesty. This is an act of extraordinary courage and extraordinary foolishness. The counting commission overrules you. The accurate results are destroyed. You have demonstrated that you cannot be trusted with sensitive political information, which is a death sentence in slow motion."},
        {text: "Say nothing about the discrepancy — you did not see what you saw.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You practice the Soviet art of unsee. The vote count never happened. The discrepancy never existed. You were never on the counting commission. In Stalin's Soviet Union, the ability to forget on command is the most essential survival skill."},
        {text: "Privately inform Stalin of the true vote count — let him decide how to handle it.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -5, survival: 0.8, response: "You bring the embarrassing results directly to Stalin. He already knows, of course — his people are everywhere. But your personal report demonstrates loyalty. Stalin's response to the vote will unfold over the coming years in the form of mass arrests and executions of Congress delegates."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Second Five-Year Plan is debated at the Congress. It promises somewhat more realistic targets than the first and includes provisions for improving consumer goods production and living standards. After the famine and the chaos of the first plan, there are genuine hopes for a period of consolidation. Some delegates speak of a 'new phase' of socialist construction — less violent, more productive.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Advocate for ambitious but achievable targets — the Second Plan should learn from the First Plan's mistakes.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You push for rational planning. The Second Five-Year Plan is indeed more balanced than the first, with greater emphasis on quality over quantity. Your constructive input contributes to a plan that will produce genuine economic growth in 1934-36, before the purges destroy the administrative apparatus."},
        {text: "Demand even higher targets than the First Plan — revolutionary momentum must not slacken.", loyalty: 10, cunning: -5, reputation: 0, survival: 0.8, response: "You call for more ambition. Some targets are indeed increased. But the exhausted economy and traumatized population cannot sustain another round of breakneck industrialization. Your maximalism impresses hardliners but contributes to unrealistic expectations."},
        {text: "Propose that the Second Plan prioritize agricultural recovery — the countryside needs investment after the devastation of collectivization.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 10, survival: 0.8, response: "You call for agricultural healing. The famine has demonstrated that destroying the countryside to feed the cities is self-defeating. Some investment in collective farm infrastructure is indeed included in the plan, though heavy industry retains priority."},
        {text: "Focus on military-industrial production — with Hitler rising in Germany and Japan expanding in the East, defense must be the priority.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You make the defense argument. With Nazi Germany and Imperial Japan as growing threats, Soviet industrial policy must prioritize military production. This strategic foresight will be vindicated by 1941, and your emphasis on defense aligns with Stalin's own growing concern about external threats."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "A new generation of party members is rising — young people who joined after the revolution, who know nothing of underground struggle and factional debate. They are products of the party schools and the Five-Year Plan. They are loyal, technically competent, and unquestioning. They see Stalin not as a faction leader who outmaneuvered rivals but as the embodiment of the party itself. The old revolutionaries view them with a mixture of hope and unease.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Mentor the young cadres — they are the future and should be guided by those who remember the revolution.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 10, survival: 0.85, response: "You take young officials under your wing. They are eager, competent, and uncritical. By mentoring them, you build a network of proteges who may protect you in the future. Many of these young cadres will replace the old guard after the purges decimate the senior ranks."},
        {text: "View the new generation with suspicion — they lack revolutionary experience and are tools of the apparatus.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 0, reputation: 5, survival: 0.7, response: "You distrust the new cadres. They are products of a system that values obedience over independent thinking. Your skepticism about the younger generation marks you as an old-fashioned revolutionary — which is increasingly a liability rather than a credential."},
        {text: "Align yourself with the rising generation — the old guard is a diminishing asset and the future belongs to the young.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You pivot toward the younger officials. They are the future leadership — some of them will survive the purges and rise to prominence under Khrushchev and Brezhnev. Your early investment in relationships with the new generation pays long-term dividends."},
        {text: "Propose reforms to party education that ensure young cadres learn genuine Marxist theory, not just catechism.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You advocate for deeper ideological education. The new generation recites formulas but does not understand dialectics. Your concern for genuine theoretical education is admirable but increasingly irrelevant — the party needs administrators, not theoreticians."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "The Congress must address the aftermath of the famine that killed millions in Ukraine, Kazakhstan, and elsewhere. Officially, the famine never happened. References to 'food difficulties' are as far as anyone dares go. Population statistics are being falsified to conceal the demographic catastrophe. The 1937 census, when it comes, will show such a population shortfall that the census-takers themselves will be arrested.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Maintain the official fiction — there was no famine, only temporary food difficulties caused by kulak sabotage.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 10, reputation: -10, survival: 0.9, response: "You repeat the lie. The famine that killed between five and seven million people officially did not happen. Kulak sabotage, bad weather, local administrative errors — these are the approved explanations. The truth will not be officially acknowledged for over fifty years."},
        {text: "Propose agricultural investment to prevent future 'food difficulties' — address the problem without acknowledging its true scale.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.9, response: "You call for measures to prevent a recurrence without naming what occurred. More tractors, better seeds, trained agronomists, grain reserves. This coded language allows you to address the catastrophe constructively while maintaining the fiction that the famine did not happen."},
        {text: "In a private conversation with a trusted colleague, express horror at what happened — you need someone to share the burden of knowledge.", loyalty: -5, cunning: -10, reputation: 5, survival: 0.65, response: "You confide in someone. The burden of complicit silence is heavy, and you need human connection. But in Stalin's Soviet Union, there are no trusted colleagues — only potential informants. Your private confession may become public evidence against you."},
        {text: "Throw yourself into work — build, plan, produce — use activity to avoid thinking about what you have witnessed.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.85, response: "You choose the path of productive denial. Many Soviet officials coped with the system's horrors by burying themselves in constructive work. Build the subway, electrify the village, meet the plan. Activity provides both meaning and distraction from moral catastrophe."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "Kirov delivers a powerful speech at the Congress that electrifies the hall. He is charismatic, confident, and genuinely popular. His Leningrad organization is a model of efficiency. Stalin watches from the presidium, his expression unreadable. In the months after the Congress, Stalin will propose that Kirov move to Moscow — closer to the center of power, or closer to danger. Kirov resists the move.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Attach yourself to Kirov's rising star — he may be the future leader of the party.", loyalty: -5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.55, response: "You cultivate a relationship with Kirov. It seems like a wise investment — he is popular, competent, and apparently favored. But Kirov will be assassinated on December 1, 1934. Those closely associated with him will face intensive investigation and, often, arrest."},
        {text: "Remain loyal to Stalin above all — Kirov is impressive but Stalin holds the apparatus.", loyalty: 10, cunning: 15, reputation: 0, survival: 0.9, response: "You recognize that popularity means nothing against the apparatus. Stalin controls the NKVD, the Secretariat, and the army. Kirov has charisma but no independent power base. Your assessment is correct — but even loyalty to Stalin provides no guarantee of survival."},
        {text: "Maintain good relations with both Stalin and Kirov — they are not yet enemies, and there is no reason to choose.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 15, reputation: 5, survival: 0.85, response: "You keep ties with both men. At this point, Stalin and Kirov are still allies, and being friendly with both is entirely natural. The crisis will come later, after the Congress. Until then, balance is the optimal strategy."},
        {text: "Distance yourself from both the Stalin and Kirov circles — stay in the middle ranks where you are less visible.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 10, reputation: 0, survival: 0.8, response: "You reduce your profile. The coming purges will target the prominent and the connected. Being a mid-ranking official in a non-sensitive area provides some protection. Invisibility is a strategy — though the purges will eventually reach even the obscure."}
      ]
    },
    {
      text: "As the Congress ends, delegates return to their regions with a sense that a new era may be beginning. Industrialization is progressing, the worst of collectivization seems past, and the party appears united. Some dare to hope for a period of normalization. They do not know that within months, Kirov's assassination will trigger a chain of events leading to the Great Terror. Of the 1,966 delegates at this Congress, 1,108 will be arrested in the coming years.",
      choices: [
        {text: "Return to your duties with cautious optimism — focus on economic construction and hope for stability.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 5, reputation: 5, survival: 0.8, response: "You go back to work hoping that the worst is over. The next few years will prove this hope tragically misplaced. But productive work provides some protection — the system needs competent administrators even during purges. Your expertise may be your shield."},
        {text: "Begin discreetly preparing for trouble — cultivate relationships with NKVD officials who might provide warning.", loyalty: 0, cunning: 15, reputation: -5, survival: 0.85, response: "You build intelligence sources within the security apparatus. Knowing when the arrests are coming and who is targeted gives you time to prepare or adjust. Some officials survive the purges precisely because they have informants inside the NKVD."},
        {text: "Compile a dossier of denunciations against potential rivals — in the coming storm, striking first may be the only defense.", loyalty: 5, cunning: 10, reputation: -15, survival: 0.75, response: "You prepare offensive material. When the purges hit, those who denounce others first sometimes survive while their targets perish. But the machinery of denunciation is indiscriminate — your victims' forced confessions may name you in turn. The purge devours its children."},
        {text: "Write private letters to family members preserving the truth about what has happened — someone should remember.", loyalty: -10, cunning: -10, reputation: 15, survival: 0.55, response: "You create a private record. It is an act of moral courage in a time of official lies. But private papers can be seized during searches, and their contents used as evidence. Some families will preserve such documents for decades, contributing to the eventual reckoning with the Soviet past."}
      ]
    }
  ],
};
